1\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAwake ye muses nine, sing me a strain divine,\u13\'0dUnwind the solemn twine, and tie my Valentine!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh the Earth was made for lovers, for damsel, and hopeless swain,\u13\'0dFor sighing, and gentle whispering, and unity made of twain. \u13\'0dAll things do go a courting, in earth, or sea, or air, \u13\'0dGod hath made nothing single but thee in His world so fair! \u13\'0dThe bride, and then the bridegroom, the two, and then the one, \u13\'0dAdam, and Eve, his consort, the moon, and then the sun; \u13\'0dThe life doth prove the precept, who obey shall happy be, \u13\'0dWho will not serve the sovereign, be hanged on fatal tree. \u13\'0dThe high do seek the lowly, the great do seek the small, \u13\'0dNone cannot find who seeketh, on this terrestrial ball; \u13\'0dThe bee doth court the flower, the flower his suit receives, \u13\'0dAnd they make merry wedding, whose guests are hundred leaves; \u13\'0dThe wind doth woo the branches, the branches they are won, \u13\'0dAnd the father fond demandeth the maiden for his son. \u13\'0dThe storm doth walk the seashore humming a mournful tune, \u13\'0dThe wave with eye so pensive, looketh to see the moon, \u13\'0dTheir spirits meet together, they make their solemn vows, \u13\'0dNo more he singeth mournful, her sadness she doth lose. \u13\'0dThe worm doth woo the mortal, death claims a living bride, \u13\'0dNight unto day is married, morn unto eventide; \u13\'0dEarth is a merry damsel, and heaven a knight so true, \u13\'0dAnd Earth is quite coquettish, and beseemeth in vain to sue. \u13\'0dNow to the application, to the reading of the roll, \u13\'0dTo bringing thee to justice, and marshalling thy soul: \u13\'0dThou art a human solo, a being cold, and lone, \u13\'0dWilt have no kind companion, thou reap'st what thou hast sown. \u13\'0dHast never silent hours, and minutes all too long, \u13\'0dAnd a deal of sad reflection, and wailing instead of song? \u13\'0dThere's Sarah, and Eliza, and Emeline so fair, \u13\'0dAnd Harriet, and Susan, and she with curling hair! \u13\'0dThine eyes are sadly blinded, but yet thou mayest see \u13\'0dSix true, and comely maidens sitting upon the tree; \u13\'0dApproach that tree with caution, then up it boldly climb, \u13\'0dAnd seize the one thou lovest, nor care for space, or time! \u13\'0dThen bear her to the greenwood, and build for her a bower, \u13\'0dAnd give her what she asketh, jewel, or bird, or flower -- \u13\'0dAnd bring the fife, and trumpet, and beat upon the drum -- \u13\'0dAnd bid the world Goodmorrow, and go to glory home!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d2\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere is another sky, \u13\'0dEver serene and fair, \u13\'0dAnd there is another sunshine, \u13\'0dThough it be darkness there; \u13\'0dNever mind faded forests, Austin, \u13\'0dNever mind silent fields - \u13\'0dHere is a little forest, \u13\'0dWhose leaf is ever green; \u13\'0dHere is a brighter garden, \u13\'0dWhere not a frost has been; \u13\'0dIn its unfading flowers \u13\'0dI hear the bright bee hum: \u13\'0dPrithee, my brother, \u13\'0dInto my garden come!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d3\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Sic transit gloria mundi,"\u13\'0d"How doth the busy bee,"\u13\'0d"Dum vivimus vivamus,"\u13\'0dI stay mine enemy!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh "veni, vidi, vici!"\u13\'0dOh caput cap-a-pie!\u13\'0dAnd oh "memento mori"\u13\'0dWhen I am far from thee!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHurrah for Peter Parley!\u13\'0dHurrah for Daniel Boone!\u13\'0dThree cheers, sir, for the gentleman\u13\'0dWho first observed the moon!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPeter, put up the sunshine;\u13\'0dPatti, arrange the stars;\u13\'0dTell Luna, tea is waiting,\u13\'0dAnd call your brother Mars!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPut down the apple, Adam,\u13\'0dAnd come away with me,\u13\'0dSo shalt thou have a pippin\u13\'0dFrom off my father's tree!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI climb the "Hill of Science,"\u13\'0dI "view the landscape o'er;"\u13\'0dSuch transcendental prospect,\u13\'0dI ne'er beheld before!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dUnto the Legislature\u13\'0dMy country bids me go;\u13\'0dI'll take my india rubbers,\u13\'0dIn case the wind should blow!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDuring my education,\u13\'0dIt was announced to me\u13\'0dThat gravitation, stumbling,\u13\'0dFell from an apple tree!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe earth upon an axis\u13\'0dWas once supposed to turn,\u13\'0dBy way of a gymnastic\u13\'0dIn honor of the sun!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt was the brave Columbus,\u13\'0dA sailing o'er the tide,\u13\'0dWho notified the nations\u13\'0dOf where I would reside!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMortality is fatal --\u13\'0dGentility is fine,\u13\'0dRascality, heroic,\u13\'0dInsolvency, sublime!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOur Fathers being weary,\u13\'0dLaid down on Bunker Hill;\u13\'0dAnd tho' full many a morning,\u13\'0dYet they are sleeping still, --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe trumpet, sir, shall wake them,\u13\'0dIn dreams I see them rise,\u13\'0dEach with a solemn musket\u13\'0dA marching to the skies!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA coward will remain, Sir,\u13\'0dUntil the fight is done;\u13\'0dBut an immortal hero\u13\'0dWill take his hat, and run!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGood bye, Sir, I am going;\u13\'0dMy country calleth me;\u13\'0dAllow me, Sir, at parting,\u13\'0dTo wipe my weeping e'e.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn token of our friendship\u13\'0dAccept this "Bonnie Doon,"\u13\'0dAnd when the hand that plucked it\u13\'0dHath passed beyond the moon,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe memory of my ashes\u13\'0dWill consolation be;\u13\'0dThen, farewell, Tuscarora,\u13\'0dAnd farewell, Sir, to thee!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d4\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOn this wondrous sea\u13\'0dSailing silently,\u13\'0dHo! Pilot, ho!\u13\'0dKnowest thou the shore\u13\'0dWhere no breakers roar --\u13\'0dWhere the storm is o'er?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn the peaceful west\u13\'0dMany the sails at rest --\u13\'0dThe anchors fast --\u13\'0dThither I pilot thee --\u13\'0dLand Ho! Eternity!\u13\'0dAshore at last!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d5\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI have a Bird in spring\u13\'0dWhich for myself doth sing --\u13\'0dThe spring decoys.\u13\'0dAnd as the summer nears --\u13\'0dAnd as the Rose appears,\u13\'0dRobin is gone.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYet do I not repine\u13\'0dKnowing that Bird of mine\u13\'0dThough flown --\u13\'0dLearneth beyond the sea\u13\'0dMelody new for me\u13\'0dAnd will return.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFast is a safer hand\u13\'0dHeld in a truer Land\u13\'0dAre mine --\u13\'0dAnd though they now depart,\u13\'0dTell I my doubting heart\u13\'0dThey're thine.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn a serener Bright,\u13\'0dIn a more golden light\u13\'0dI see\u13\'0dEach little doubt and fear,\u13\'0dEach little discord here\u13\'0dRemoved.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen will I not repine,\u13\'0dKnowing that Bird of mine\u13\'0dThough flown\u13\'0dShall in a distant tree\u13\'0dBright melody for me\u13\'0dReturn.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d6\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFrequently the wood are pink --\u13\'0dFrequently are brown.\u13\'0dFrequently the hills undress\u13\'0dBehind my native town.\u13\'0dOft a head is crested I was wont to see --\u13\'0dAnd as oft a cranny Where it used to be --\u13\'0dAnd the Earth -- they tell me --\u13\'0dOn its Axis turned!\u13\'0dWonderful Rotation!\u13\'0dBy but twelve performed!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d7\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe feet of people walking home With gayer sandals go - The Crocus -- till she rises The Vassal of the snow -- The lips at Hallelujah Long years of practise bore Till bye and bye these Bargemen Walked singing on the shore.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPearls are the Diver's farthings Extorted from the Sea -- Pinions -- the Seraph's wagon Pedestrian once -- as we -- Night is the morning's Canvas Larceny -- legacy -- Death, but our rapt attention To Immortality.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy figures fail to tell me How far the Village lies - Whose peasants are the Angels -- Whose Cantons dot the skies -- My Classics veil their faces -- My faith that Dark adores -- Which from its solemn abbeys Such resurection pours. There is a word Which bears a sword Can pierce an armed man -- It hurls its barbed syllables And is mute again -- But where it fell The saved will tell On patriotic day, Some epauletted Brother Gave his breath away.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWherever runs the breathless sun -- Wherever roams the day -- There is its noiseless onset -- There is its victory! Behold the keenest marksman! The most accomplished shot! Time's sublimest target Is a soul "forgot!"\u13\'0d\u13\'0d9\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThrough lane it lay -- through bramble -- Through clearing and through wood -- Banditti often passed us Upon the lonely road.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe wolf came peering curious -- The owl looked puzzled down -- The serpent's satin figure Glid stealthily along --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe tempests touched our garments -- The lightning's poinards gleamed -- Fierce from the Crag above us The hungry Vulture screamed --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe satyr's fingers beckoned -- The valley murmured "Come" -- These were the mates -- This was the road Those children fluttered home. 10\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy wheel is in the dark! I cannot see a spoke Yet know its dripping feet Go round and round.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy foot is on the Tide! An unfrequented road -- Yet have all roads A clearing at the end --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome have resigned the Loom -- Some in the busy tomb Find quaint employ --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome with new -- stately feet -- Pass royal through the gate -- Flinging the problem back At you and I!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d11\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI never told the buried gold Upon the hill -- that lies - I saw the sun -- his plunder done Crouch low to guard his prize.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe stood as near As stood you here -- A pace had been between -- Did but a snake bisect the brake My life had forfeit been.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat was a wondrous booty -- I hope 'twas honest gained. Those were the fairest ingots That ever kissed the spade!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhether to keep the secret -- Whether to reveal -- Whether as I ponder Kidd will sudden sail --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCould a shrewd advise me We might e'en divide -- Should a shrewd betray me -- Atropos decide!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d12\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe morns are meeker than they were -- The nuts are getting brown -- The berry's cheek is plumper -- The Rose is out of town.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Maple wears a gayer scarf -- The field a scarlet gown -- Lest I should be old fashioned I'll put a trinket on.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d13\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSleep is supposed to be By souls of sanity The shutting of the eye.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSleep is the station grand Down which, on either hand The hosts of witness stand!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMorn is supposed to be By people of degree The breaking of the Day.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMorning has not occurred!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat shall Aurora be -- East of Eternity -- One with the banner gay -- One in the red array -- That is the break of Day!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d14\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOne Sister have I in our house, And one, a hedge away. There's only one recorded, But both belong to me.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOne came the road that I came -- And wore my last year's gown -- The other, as a bird her nest, Builded our hearts among.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe did not sing as we did -- It was a different tune -- Herself to her a music As Bumble bee of June.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dToday is far from Childhood -- But up and down the hills I held her hand the tighter -- Which shortened all the miles --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd still her hum The years among, Deceives the Butterfly; Still in her Eye The Violets lie Mouldered this many May.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI spilt the dew -- But took the morn -- I chose this single star From out the wide night's numbers -- Sue - forevermore!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d15 The Guest is gold and crimson -- An Opal guest and gray -- Of Ermine is his doublet -- His Capuchin gay --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe reaches town at nightfall -- He stops at every door -- Who looks for him at morning I pray him too -- explore The Lark's pure territory -- Or the Lapwing's shore!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d16\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI would distil a cup, And bear to all my friends, Drinking to her no more astir, By beck, or burn, or moor!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d17\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBaffled for just a day}
