or two -- Embarrassed -- not afraid -- Encounter in my garden An unexpected Maid.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe beckons, and the woods start -She nods, and all begin -- Surely, such a country I was never in!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d18\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Gentian weaves her fringes -- The Maple's loom is red -- My departing blossoms Obviate parade. A brief, but patient illness -- An hour to prepare, And one below this morning Is where the angels are -It was a short procession, The Bobolink was there -- An aged Bee addressed us -- And then we knelt in prayer -- We trust that she was willing -- We ask that we may be. Summer -- Sister -- Seraph! Let us go with thee!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn the name of the Bee -- And of the Butterfly -- And of the Breeze -- Amen!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d19\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA sepal, petal, and a thorn Upon a common summer's morn -- A flask of Dew -- A Bee or two -- A Breeze -- a caper in the trees -- And I'm a Rose!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d20\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDistrustful of the Gentian -- And just to turn away, The fluttering of her fringes Child my perfidy -- Weary for my ---------- I will singing go -- I shall not feel the sleet -- then -- I shall not fear the snow.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFlees so the phantom meadow Before the breathless Bee -- So bubble brooks in deserts On Ears that dying lie -- Burn so the Evening Spires To Eyes that Closing go -- Hangs so distant Heaven -- To a hand below.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d21\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe lose -- because we win -- Gamblers -- recollecting which Toss their dice again!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d22\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAll these my banners be. I sow my pageantry In May -- It rises train by train -- Then sleeps in state again -- My chancel -- all the plain Today.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo lose -- if one can find again -- To miss -- if one shall meet -- The Burglar cannot rob -- then -- The Broker cannot cheat. So build the hillocks gaily Thou little spade of mine Leaving nooks for Daisy And for Columbine -- You and I the secret Of the Crocus know -- Let us chant it softly -- "There is no more snow!"\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo him who keeps an Orchis' heart -The swamps are pink with June. I had a guinea golden - I lost it in the sand -- And tho' the sum was simple And pounds were in the land -- Still, had it such a value Unto my frugal eye -- That when I could not find it -- I sat me down to sigh.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI had a crimson Robin -- Who sang full many a day But when the woods were painted, He, too, did fly away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTime brought me other Robins -- Their ballads were the same -- Still, for my missing Troubador I kept the "house at hame."\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI had a star in heaven -- One "Pleiad" was its name -- And when I was not heeding, It wandered from the same. And tho' the skies are crowded -- And all the night ashine - I do not care about it -- Since none of them are mine.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy story has a moral -- I have a missing friend -"Pleiad" its name, and Robin, And guinea in the sand. And when this mournful ditty Accompanied with tear -- Shall meet the eye of traitor In country far from here -- Grant that repentance solemn May seize upon his mind -- And he no consolation Beneath the sun may find. There is a morn by men unseen -- Whose maids upon remoter green Keep their Seraphic May -- And all day long, with dance and game, And gambol I may never name -- Employ their holiday.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHere to light measure, move the feet Which walk no more the village street -- Nor by the wood are found -- Here are the birds that sought the sun When last year's distaff idle hung And summer's brows were bound.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNe'er saw I such a wondrous scene -- Ne'er such a ring on such a green -- Nor so serene array -- As if the stars some summer night Should swing their cups of Chrysolite -- And revel till the day --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLike thee to dance -- like thee to sing -- People upon the mystic green -- I ask, each new May Morn. I wait thy far, fantastic bells -- Unto the different dawn!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d25\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe slept beneath a tree -- Remembered but by me. I touched her Cradle mute -- She recognized the foot -- Put on her carmine suit And see!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d26\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt's all I have to bring today -- This, and my heart beside -- This, and my heart, and all the fields -- And all the meadows wide -- Be sure you count -- should I forget Some one the sum could tell -- This, and my heart, and all the Bees Which in the Clover dwell.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d27\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMorns like these -- we parted -- Noons like these -- she rose -- Fluttering first -- then firmer To her fair repose.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNever did she lisp it -- It was not for me -- She -- was mute from transport -- I -- from agony --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTill -- the evening nearing One the curtains drew -- Quick! A Sharper rustling! And this linnet flew!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d28\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo has a Daisy vanished From the fields today -- So tiptoed many a slipper To Paradise away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOozed so in crimson bubbles Day's departing tide -- Blooming -- tripping -- flowing Are ye then with God?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d29\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf those I loved were lost The Crier's voice would tell me -- If those I loved were found The bells of Ghent would ring --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDid those I loved repose The Daisy would impel me. Philip -- when bewildered Bore his riddle in!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d30\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAdrift! A little boat adrift! And night is coming down! Will no one guide a little boat Unto the nearest town?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo Sailors say -- on yesterday -- Just as the dusk was brown One little boat gave up its strife And gurgled down and down.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo angels say -- on yesterday -- Just as the dawn was red One little boat -- o'erspent with gales -- Retrimmed its masts -- redecked its sails -- And shot -- exultant on!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d31\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSummer for thee, grant I may be When Summer days are flown! Thy music still, when Whipporwill And Oriole -- are done!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor thee to bloom, I'll skip the tomb And row my blossoms o'er! Pray gather me -- Anemone -- Thy flower -- forevermore! 32\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen Roses cease to bloom, Sir, And Violets are done -- When Bumblebees in solemn flight Have passed beyond the Sun -- The hand that paused to gather Upon this Summer's day Will idle lie -- in Auburn -- Then take my flowers -- pray!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d33\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf recollecting were forgetting, Then I remember not. And if forgetting, recollecting, How near I had forgot. And if to miss, were merry, And to mourn, were gay, How very blithe the fingers That gathered this, Today!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d34\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGarland for Queens, may be -- Laurels -- for rare degree Of soul or sword. Ah -- but remembering me -- Ah -- but remembering thee -- Nature in chivalry -- Nature in charity -- Nature in equity -- This Rose ordained! Nobody knows this little Rose -- It might a pilgrim be Did I not take it from the ways And lift it up to thee. Only a Bee will miss it - Only a Butterfly, Hastening from far journey -- On its breast to lie -- Only a Bird will wonder -- Only a Breeze will sigh - Ah Little Rose -- how easy For such as thee to die!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d36 Snow flakes.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI counted till they danced so Their slippers leaped the town, And then I took a pencil To note the rebels down. And then they grew so jolly I did resign the prig, And ten of my once stately toes Are marshalled for a jig!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d37\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBefore the ice is in the pools -- Before the skaters go, Or any check at nightfall Is tarnished by the snow --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBefore the fields have finished, Before the Christmas tree, Wonder upon wonder Will arrive to me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat we touch the hems of On a summer's day -- What is only walking Just a bridge away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat which sings so -- speaks so -When there's no one here -- Will the frock I wept in Answer me to wear?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d38\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy such and such an offering To Mr. So and So, The web of live woven -- So martyrs albums show!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d39\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt did not surprise me -- So I said -- or thought -- She will stir her pinions And the nest forgot,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTraverse broader forests -- Build in gayer boughs, Breathe in Ear more modern God's old fashioned vows --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis was but a Birdling -What and if it be One within my bosom Had departed me?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis was but a story -- What and if indeed There were just such coffin In the heart instead? When I count the seeds That are sown beneath, To bloom so, bye and bye --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen I con the people Lain so low, To be received as high -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen I believe the garden Mortal shall not see -- Pick by faith its blossom And avoid its Bee, I can spare this summer, unreluctantly.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d41\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI robbed the Woods -- The trusting Woods. The unsuspecting Trees Brought out their Burs and mosses My fantasy to please. I scanned their trinkets curious -- I grasped -- I bore away -- What will the solemn Hemlock -- What will the Oak tree say?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d42\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Day! Help! Help! Another Day! Your prayers, oh Passer by! From such a common ball as this Might date a Victory! From marshallings as simple The flags of nations swang. Steady -- my soul: What issues Upon thine arrow hang!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d43\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCould live -- did live -- Could die -- did die -- Could smile upon the whole Through faith in one he met not, To introduce his soul.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCould go from scene familiar To an untraversed spot -- Could contemplate the journey With unpuzzled heart -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSuch trust had one among us, Among us not today -- We who saw the launching Never sailed the Bay!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d44\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf she had been the Mistletoe And I had been the Rose -- How gay upon your table My velvet life to close - Since I am of the Druid, And she is of the dew -- I'll deck Tradition's buttonhole -- And send the Rose to you.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d45\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere's something quieter than sleep Within this inner room! It wears a sprig upon its breast -- And will not tell its name.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome touch it, and some kiss it -- Some chafe its idle hand -- It has a simple gravity I do not understand!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI would not weep if I were they -- How rude in one to sob! Might scare the quiet fairy Back to her native wood! While simple-hearted neighbors Chat of the "Early dead" -- We -- prone to periphrasis Remark that Birds have fled!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d46\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI keep my pledge. I was not called -- Death did not notice me. I bring my Rose. I plight again, By every sainted Bee -- By Daisy called from hillside -- by Bobolink from lane. Blossom and I -- Her oath, and mine -- Will surely come again.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d47\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHeart! We will forget him! You and I -- tonight! You may forget the warmth he gave -- I will forget the light!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen you have done, pray tell me That I may straight begin! Haste! lest while you're lagging I remember him!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d48\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOnce more, my now bewildered Dove Bestirs}
