her puzzled wings Once more her mistress, on the deep Her troubled question flings -- Thrice to the floating casement The Patriarch's bird returned, Courage! My brave Columbia! There may yet be land\u13\'0d\u13\'0d49\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI never lost as much but twice, And that was in the sod. Twice have I stood a beggar Before the door of God!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAngels -- twice descending Reimbursed my store -- Burglar! Banker -- Father! I am poor once more!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d50\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI haven't told my garden yet -- Lest that should conquer me. I haven't quite the strength now To break it to the Bee --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI will not name it in the street For shops would stare at me -- That one so shy -- so ignorant Should have the face to die.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe hillsides must not know it -- Where I have rambled so -- Nor tell the loving forests The day that I shall go -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNor lisp it at the table -Nor heedless by the way Hint that within the Riddle One will walk today -- I often passed the village When going home from school -- And wondered what they did there -- And why it was so still -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI did not know the year then -- In which my call would come -- Earlier, by the Dial, Than the rest have gone.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt's stiller than the sundown. It's cooler than the dawn -- The Daisies dare to come here -- And birds can flutter down --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo when you are tired -Or perplexed -- or cold -- Trust the loving promise Underneath the mould, Cry "it's I," "take Dollie," And I will enfold!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d52\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhether my bark went down at sea -- Whether she met with gales -- Whether to isles enchanted She bent her docile sails --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy what mystic mooring She is held today -- This is the errand of the eye Out upon the Bay.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d53 Taken from men -- this morning -- Carried by men today -- Met by the Gods with banners -- Who marshalled her away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOne little maid -- from playmates -- One little mind from school -- There must be guests in Eden -- All the rooms are full --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFar -- as the East from Even -- Dim -- as the border star -- Courtiers quaint, in Kingdoms Our departed are.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d54\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I should die, And you should live -- And time should gurgle on -- And morn should beam -- And noon should burn - As it has usual done - If Birds should build as early And Bees as bustling go -- One might depart at option From enterprise below! 'Tis sweet to know that stocks will stand When we with Daisies lie -- That Commerce will continue -- And Trades as briskly fly -- It makes the parting tranquil And keeps the soul serene -- That gentlemen so sprightly Conduct the pleasing scene!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d55\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy Chivalries as tiny, A Blossom, or a Book, The seeds of smiles are planted -- Which blossom in the dark. If I should cease to bring a Rose Upon a festal day, 'Twill be because beyond the Rose I have been called away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I should cease to take the names My buds commemorate -- 'Twill be because Death's finger Claps my murmuring lip!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d57\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo venerate the simple days Which lead the seasons by, Needs but to remember That from you or I, They may take the trifle Termed mortality!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d58\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDelayed till she had ceased to know -- Delayed till in its vest of snow Her loving bosom lay -- An hour behind the fleeting breath -- Later by just an hour than Death -- Oh lagging Yesterday!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCould she have guessed that it would be -- Could but a crier of the joy Have climbed the distant hill -- Had not the bliss so slow a pace Who knows but this surrendered face Were undefeated still?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh if there may departing be Any forgot by Victory In her imperial round -- Show them this meek appareled thing That could not stop to be a king -- Doubtful if it be crowned!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d59\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA little East of Jordan, Evangelists record, A Gymnast and an Angel Did wrestle long and hard --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTill morning touching mountain -- And Jacob, waxing strong, The Angel begged permission To Breakfast -- to return --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNot so, said cunning Jacob! "I will not let thee go Except thou bless me" -- Stranger! The which acceded to -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLight swung the silver fleeces "Peniel" Hills beyond, And the bewildered Gymnast Found he had worsted God!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d60\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLike her the Saints retire, In their Chapeaux of fire, Martial as she!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLike her the Evenings steal Purple and Cochineal After the Day!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Departed" -- both -- they say! i.e. gathered away, Not found,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dArgues the Aster still -Reasons the Daffodil Profound!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d61\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPapa above! Regard a Mouse O'erpowered by the Cat! Reserve within thy kingdom A "Mansion" for the Rat!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSnug in seraphic Cupboards To nibble all the day While unsuspecting Cycles Wheel solemnly away!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d62\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Sown in dishonor"! Ah! Indeed! May this "dishonor" be? If I were half so fine myself I'd notice nobody!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Sown in corruption"! Not so fast! Apostle is askew! Corinthians 1. 15. narrates A Circumstance or two!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d63\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf pain for peace prepares Lo, what "Augustan" years Our feet await! If springs from winter rise, Can the Anemones Be reckoned up?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf night stands fast -- then noon To gird us for the sun, What gaze!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen from a thousand skies On our developed eyes Noons blaze!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d64\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome Rainbow -- coming from the Fair! Some Vision of the World Cashmere -- I confidently see! Or else a Peacock's purple Train Feather by feather -- on the plain Fritters itself away!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe dreamy Butterflies bestir! Lethargic pools resume the whir Of last year's sundered tune! From some old Fortress on the sun Baronial Bees -- march -- one by one -- In murmuring platoon!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Robins stand as thick today As flakes of snow stood yesterday -- On fence -- and Roof -- and Twig! The Orchis binds her feather on For her old lover - Don the Sun! Revisiting the Bog!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWithout Commander! Countless! Still! The Regiments of Wood and Hill In bright detachment stand! Behold! Whose Multitudes are these? The children of whose turbaned seas -- Or what Circassian Land? I can't tell you -- but you feel it -- Nor can you tell me -- Saints, with ravished slate and pencil Solve our April Day!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSweeter than a vanished frolic From a vanished green! Swifter than the hoofs of Horsemen Round a Ledge of dream!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dModest, let us walk among it With our faces veiled -- As they say polite Archangels Do in meeting God!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNot for me -- to prate about it! Not for you -- to say To some fashionable Lady "Charming April Day"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dRather -- Heaven's "Peter Parley"! By which Children slow To sublimer Recitation Are prepared to go!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d66\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo from the mould Scarlet and Gold Many a Bulb will rise -- Hidden away, cunningly, From sagacious eyes.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo from Cocoon Many a Worm Leap so Highland gay, Peasants like me, Peasants like Thee Gaze perplexedly! Success is counted sweetest By those who ne'er succeed. To comprehend a nectar Requires sorest need.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNot one of all the purple Host Who took the Flag today Can tell the definition So clear of Victory\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs he defeated -- dying -- On whose forbidden ear The distant strains of triumph Burst agonized and clear!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d68\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAmbition cannot find him. Affection doesn't know How many leagues of nowhere Lie between them now.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYesterday, undistinguished! Eminent Today For our mutual hone, Immortality!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d69\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLow at my problem bending, Another problem comes -- Larger than mine -- Serener -- Involving statelier sums.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI check my busy pencil, My figures file away. Wherefore, my baffled fingers They perplexity? "Arcturus" is his other name -- I'd rather call him "Star." It's very mean of Science To go and interfere!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI slew a worm the other day -- A "Savant" passing by Murmured "Resurgam" -- "Centipede"! "Oh Lord -- how frail are we"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI pull a flower from the woods -- A monster with a glass Computes the stamens in a breath -And has her in a "class"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhereas I took the Butterfly Aforetime in my hat -- He sits erect in "Cabinets" -- The Clover bells forgot.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat once was "Heaven" Is "Zenith" now -- Where I proposed to go When Time's brief masquerade was done Is mapped and charted too.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat if the poles should frisk about And stand upon their heads! I hope I'm ready for "the worst" -- Whatever prank betides!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps the "Kingdom of Heaven's" changed -I hope the "Children" there Won't be "new fashioned" when I come -- And laugh at me -- and stare --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI hope the Father in the skies Will lift his little girl -- Old fashioned -- naught -- everything -- Over the stile of "Pearl." A throe upon the features -- A hurry in the breath -- An ecstasy of parting Denominated "Death" --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAn anguish at the mention Which when to patience grown, I've known permission given To rejoin its own.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d72\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGlowing is her Bonnet, Glowing is her Cheek, Glowing is her Kirtle, Yet she cannot speak.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBetter as the Daisy From the Summer hill Vanish unrecorded Save by tearful rill --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSave by loving sunrise Looking for her face. Save by feet unnumbered Pausing at the place.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d73\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWho never lost, are unprepared A Coronet to find! Who never thirsted Flagons, and Cooling Tamarind!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWho never climbed the weary league -- Can such a foot explore The purple territories On Pizarro's shore?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow many Legions overcome -- The Emperor will say? How many Colors taken On Revolution Day?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow many Bullets bearest? Hast Thou the Royal scar? Angels! Write "Promoted" On this Soldier's brow!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d74\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Lady red -- amid the Hill Her annual secret keeps! A Lady white, within the Field In placid Lily sleeps!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe tidy Breezes, with their Brooms -- Sweep vale -- and hill -- and tree! Prithee, My pretty Housewives! Who may expected be?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Neighbors do not yet suspect! The Woods exchange a smile! Orchard, and Buttercup, and Bird -- In such a little while!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd yet, how still the Landscape stands! How nonchalant the Hedge! As if the "Resurrection" Were nothing very strange!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d75\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe died at play, Gambolled away Her lease of spotted hours, Then sank as gaily as a Turn Upon a Couch of flowers.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer ghost strolled softly o'er the hill Yesterday, and Today, Her vestments as the silver fleece -- Her countenance as spray.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d76\u13\'0d\u13\'0dExultation is the going Of an inland soul to sea, Past the houses -- past the headlands -- Into deep Eternity --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBred as we, among the mountains, Can the sailor understand}
