The divine intoxication Of the first league out from land?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d77\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI never hear the word "escape" Without a quicker blood, A sudden expectation A flying attitude!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI never hear of prisons broad By soldiers battered down, But I tug childish at my bars Only to fail again!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d78\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA poor -- torn heart -- a tattered heart -- That sat it down to rest -- Nor noticed that the Ebbing Day Flowed silver to the West -- Nor noticed Night did soft descend -Nor Constellation burn - Intent upon the vision Of latitudes unknown.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe angels -- happening that way This dusty heart espied - Tenderly took it up from toil And carried it to God -- There -- sandals for the Barefoot -- There -- gathered from the gales -- Do the blue havens by the hand Lead the wandering Sails.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d79\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGoing to Heaven! I don't know when -- Pray do not ask me how! Indeed I'm too astonished To think of answering you! Going to Heaven! How dim it sounds! And yet it will be done As sure as flocks go home at night Unto the Shepherd's arm!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps you're going too! Who knows? If you should get there first Save just a little space for me Close to the two I lost - The smallest "Robe" will fit me And just a bit of "Crown" -- For you know we do not mind our dress When we are going home --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'm glad I don't believe it For it would stop my breath -- And I'd like to look a little more At such a curious Earth! I'm glad they did believe it Whom I have never found Since the might Autumn afternoon I left them in the ground. Our lives are Swiss -- So still -- so Cool -- Till some odd afternoon The Alps neglect their Curtains And we look farther on!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dItaly stands the other side! While like a guard between -- The solemn Alps -- The siren Alps Forever intervene!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d81\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe should not mind so small a flower -- Except it quiet bring Our little garden that we lost Back to the Lawn again.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo spicy her Carnations nod -- So drunken, reel her Bees -- So silver steal a hundred flutes From out a hundred trees --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat whoso sees this little flower By faith may clear behold The Bobolinks around the throne And Dandelions gold.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d82\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhose cheek is this? What rosy face Has lost a blush today? I found her -- "pleiad" -- in the woods And bore her safe away. Robins, in the tradition Did cover such with leaves, But which the cheek -- And which the pall My scrutiny deceives.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d83\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHeart, not so heavy as mine Wending late home -- As it passed my window Whistled itself a tune - A careless snatch -- a ballad -- A ditty of the street -- Yet to my irritated Ear An Anodyne so sweet - It was as if a Bobolink Sauntering this way Carolled, and paused, and carolled - Then bubbled slow away! It was as if a chirping brook Upon a dusty way -- Set bleeding feet to minuets Without the knowing why! Tomorrow, night will come again -- Perhaps, weary and sore -- Ah Bugle! By my window I pray you pass once more.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d84\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer breast is fit for pearls, But I was not a "Diver" -- Her brow is fit for thrones But I have not a crest. Her heart is fit for home -- I -- a Sparrow -- build there Sweet of twigs and twine My perennial nest. "They have not chosen me," he said, "But I have chosen them!" Brave -- Broken hearted statement -- Uttered in Bethlehem!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI could not have told it, But since Jesus dared -Sovereign! Know a Daisy They dishonor shared!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d86\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSouth Winds jostle them -- Bumblebees come -- Hover -- hesitate -- Drink, and are gone --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dButterflies pause On their passage Cashmere -- I -- softly plucking, Present them here!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d87\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA darting fear -- a pomp -- a tear -- A waking on a morn To find that what one waked for, Inhales the different dawn.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d88\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs by the dead we love to sit, Become so wondrous dear -- As for the lost we grapple Tho' all the rest are here --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn broken mathematics We estimate our prize Vast -- in its fading ration To our penurious eyes!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d89\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome things that fly there be -- Birds -- Hours -- the Bumblebee -- Of these no Elegy.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome things that stay there be -- Grief -- Hills -- Eternity -- Nor this behooveth me.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere are that resting, rise. Can I expound the skies? How still the Riddle lies!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d90\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWithin my reach! I could have touched! I might have chanced that way! Soft sauntered thro' the village -- Sauntered as soft away! So unsuspected Violets Within the meadows go -- Too late for striving fingers That passed, an hour ago!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d91\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo bashful when I spied her! So pretty -- so ashamed! So hidden in her leaflets Lest anybody find --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo breathless till I passed here -- So helpless when I turned And bore her struggling, blushing, Her simple haunts beyond!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor whom I robbed the Dingle -- For whom I betrayed the Dell -- Many, will doubtless ask me, But I shall never tell!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d92\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy friend must be a Bird -- Because it flies! Mortal, my friend must be, Because it dies! Barbs has it, like a Bee! Ah, curious friend! Thou puzzlest me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d93\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWent up a year this evening! I recollect it well! Amid no bells nor bravoes The bystanders will tell! Cheerful -- as to the village -- Tranquil -- as to repose - Chastened -- as to the Chapel This humble Tourist rose! Did not talk of returning! Alluded to no time When, were the gales propitious -- We might look for him! Was grateful for the Roses In life's diverse bouquet - Talked softly of new species To pick another day; Beguiling thus the wonder The wondrous nearer drew -- Hands bustled at the moorings -- The crown respectful grew -- Ascended from our vision To Countenances new! A Difference -- A Daisy -- Is all the rest I knew!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d94\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAngels, in the early morning May be seen the Dews among, Stooping -- plucking -- smiling -- flying -- Do the Buds to them belong?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAngels, when the sun is hottest May be seen the sands among, Stooping -- plucking -- sighing -- flying -- Parched the flowers they bear along.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d95\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy nosegays are for Captives -- Dim -- expectant eyes, Fingers denied the plucking, Patient till Paradise.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo such, if they should whisper Of morning and the moor, They bear no other errand, And I, no other prayer.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d96\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSexton! My Master's sleeping here. Pray lead me to his bed! I came to build the Bird's nest, And sow the Early seed --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat when the snow creeps slowly From off his chamber door -- Daisies point the way there -- And the Troubadour.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d97\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe rainbow never tells me That gust and storm are by, Yet is she more convincing Than Philosophy.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy flowers turn from Forums -- Yet eloquent declare What Cato couldn't prove me Except the birds were here!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d98\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOne dignity delays for all -- One mitred Afternoon -- None can avoid this purple -- None evade this Crown!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCoach, it insures, and footmen -- Chamber, and state, and throng -- Bells, also, in the village As we ride grand along!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat dignified Attendants! What service when we pause! How loyally at parting Their hundred hats they raise!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer pomp surpassing ermine When simple You, and I, Present our meek escutcheon And claim the rank to die! 99\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNew feet within my garden go -- New fingers stir the sod - A Troubadour upon the Elm Betrays the solitude.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNew children play upon the green -- New Weary sleep below -- And still the pensive Spring returns -And still the punctual snow!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPoems No. 100-199\u13\'0d\u13\'0d100\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA science -- so the Savants say, "Comparative Anatomy" -- By which a single bone -- Is made a secret to unfold Of some rare tenant of the mold, Else perished in the stone --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo to the eye prospective led, This meekest flower of the mead Upon a winter's day, Stands representative in gold Of Rose and Lily, manifold, And countless Butterfly!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d101\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWill there really be a "Morning"? Is there such a thing as "Day"? Could I see it from the mountains If I were as tall as they?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHas it feet like Water lilies? Has it feathers like a Bird? Is it brought from famous countries Of which I have never heard?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh some Scholar! Oh some Sailor! Oh some Wise Men from the skies! Please to tell a little Pilgrim Where the place called "Morning" lies!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d102\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGreat Caesar! Condescend The Daisy, to receive, Gathered by Cato's Daughter, With your majestic leave!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d103\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI have a King, who does not speak -So -- wondering -- thro' the hours meek I trudge the day away -- Half glad when it is night, and sleep, If, haply, thro' a dream, to peep In parlors, shut by day.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd if I do -- when morning comes -- It is as if a hundred drums Did round my pillow roll, And shouts fill all my Childish sky, And Bells keep saying "Victory" From steeples in my soul!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd if I don't -- the little Bird Within the Orchard, is not heard, And I omit to pray "Father, thy will be done" today For my will goes the other way, And it were perjury!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d104\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhere I have lost, I softer tread -- I sow sweet flower from garden bed -- I pause above that vanished head And mourn.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhom I have lost, I pious guard From accent harsh, or ruthless word -- Feeling as if their pillow heard, Though stone!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen I have lost, you'll know by this -- A Bonnet black -- A dusk surplice -A little tremor in my voice Like this!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhy, I have lost, the people know Who dressed in flocks of purest snow Went home a century ago Next Bliss!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d105\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo hang our head -- ostensibly -- And subsequent, to find That such was not the posture Of our immortal mind --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAffords the sly presumption That in so dense a fuzz -- You -- too -- take Cobweb attitudes Upon a plane of Gauze!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d106\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Daisy follows soft the Sun -- And when his golden walk is done -Sits shyly at his feet -- He -- waking -- finds the flower there -- Wherefore -- Marauder -- art thou here? Because, Sir, love is sweet!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe are the Flower -- Thou the Sun! Forgive us, if as days decline -- We nearer steal to Thee! Enamored of the parting West -- The peace -- the flight -- the Amethyst -- Night's possibility!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d107 'Twas such a little -- little boat That toddled down the bay! 'Twas such a gallant -- gallant sea That beckoned it away!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Twas such a greedy, greedy wave That licked it from the Coast -- Nor ever guessed the stately sails My little craft was lost!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d108\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSurgeons}
