must be very careful When they take the knife! Underneath their fine incisions Stirs the Culprit -- Life!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d109\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy a flower -- By a letter -- By a nimble love -- If I weld the Rivet faster -- Final fast -- above --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNever mind my breathless Anvil! Never mind Repose! Never mind the sooty faces Tugging at the Forge!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d110\u13\'0d\u13\'0dArtists wrestled here! Lo, a tint Cashmere! Lo, a Rose! Student of the Year! For the easel here Say Repose! The Bee is not afraid of me. I know the Butterfly. The pretty people in the Woods Receive me cordially --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Brooks laugh louder when I come -- The Breezes madder play; Wherefore mine eye thy silver mists, Wherefore, Oh Summer's Day?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d112\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhere bells no more affright the morn -- Where scrabble never comes -- Where very nimble Gentlemen Are forced to keep their rooms --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhere tired Children placid sleep Thro' Centuries of noon This place is Bliss -- this town is Heaven -- Please, Pater, pretty soon!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Oh could we climb where Moses stood, And view the Landscape o'er" Not Father's bells -- nor Factories, Could scare us any more!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d113\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOur share of night to bear -- Our share of morning -- Our blank in bliss to fill Our blank in scorning -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHere a star, and there a star, Some lose their way! Here a mist, and there a mist, Afterwards -- Day! Good night, because we must, How intricate the dust! I would go, to know! Oh incognito! Saucy, Saucy Seraph To elude me so! Father! they won't tell me, Won't you tell them to?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d115\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat Inn is this Where for the night Peculiar Traveller comes? Who is the Landlord? Where the maids? Behold, what curious rooms! No ruddy fires on the hearth -- No brimming Tankards flow -- Necromancer! Landlord! Who are these below?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d116\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI had some things that I called mine -- And God, that he called his, Till, recently a rival Claim Disturbed these amities.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe property, my garden, Which having sown with care, He claims the pretty acre, And sends a Bailiff there.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe station of the parties Forbids publicity, But Justice is sublimer Than arms, or pedigree.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'll institute an "Action" -- I'll vindicate the law -- Jove! Choose your counsel -- I retain "Shaw"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d117\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn rags mysterious as these The shining Courtiers go -- Veiling the purple, and the plumes -- Veiling the ermine so.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSmiling, as they request an alms -- At some imposing door! Smiling when we walk barefoot Upon their golden floor!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d118\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy friend attacks my friend! Oh Battle picturesque! Then I turn Soldier too, And he turns Satirist! How martial is this place! Had I a mighty gun I think I'd shoot the human race And then to glory run!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d119\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTalk with prudence to a Beggar Of "Potose," and the mines! Reverently, to the Hungry Of your viands, and your wines!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCautious, hint to any Captive You have passed enfranchised feet! Anecdotes of air in Dungeons Have sometimes proved deadly sweet!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d120\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf this is "fading" Oh let me immediately "fade"! If this is "dying" Bury me, in such a shroud of red! If this is "sleep," On such a night How proud to shut the eye! Good Evening, gentle Fellow men! Peacock presumes to die!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d121\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs Watchers hang upon the East, As Beggars revel at a feast By savory Fancy spread -- As brooks in deserts babble sweet On ear too far for the delight, Heaven beguiles the tired.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs that same watcher, when the East Opens the lid of Amethyst And lets the morning go -- That Beggar, when an honored Guest, Those thirsty lips to flagons pressed, Heaven to us, if true.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d122\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA something in a summer's Day As slow her flambeaux burn away Which solemnizes me. A something in a summer's noon -- A depth -- an Azure -- a perfume -- Transcending ecstasy.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd still within a summer's night A something so transporting bright I clap my hands to see -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen veil my too inspecting face Lets such a subtle -- shimmering grace Flutter too far for me -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe wizard fingers never rest -- The purple brook within the breast Still chafes it narrow bed --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dStill rears the East her amber Flag -- Guides still the sun along the Crag His Caravan of Red --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo looking on -- the night -- the morn Conclude the wonder gay -- And I meet, coming thro' the dews Another summer's Day!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d123\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMany cross the Rhine In this cup of mine. Sip old Frankfort air From my brown Cigar.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d124\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn lands I never saw -- they say Immortal Alps look down -- Whose Bonnets touch the firmament -- Whose Sandals touch the town --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMeek at whose everlasting feet A Myriad Daisy play -- Which, Sir, are you and which am I Upon an August day?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d125\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor each ecstatic instant We must an anguish pay In keen and quivering ration To the ecstasy.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor each beloved hour Sharp pittances of years -- Bitter contested farthings -- And Coffers heaped with Tears!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d126\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo fight aloud, is very brave -- But gallanter, I know Who charge within the bosom The Cavalry of Woe --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWho win, and nations do not see -- Who fall -- and none observe -- Whose dying eyes, no Country Regards with patriot love --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe trust, in plumed procession For such, the Angels go -- Rank after Rank, with even feet -- And Uniforms of Snow.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d127\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Houses" -- so the Wise Men tell me -- "Mansions"! Mansions must be warm! Mansions cannot let the tears in, Mansions must exclude the storm!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Many Mansions," by "his Father," I don't know him; snugly built! Could the Children find the way there -- Some, would even trudge tonight!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d128\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBring me the sunset in a cup, Reckon the morning's flagons up And say how many Dew, Tell me how far the morning leaps -Tell me what time the weaver sleeps Who spun the breadth of blue!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWrite me how many notes there be In the new Robin's ecstasy Among astonished boughs -- How many trips the Tortoise makes -- How many cups the Bee partakes, The Debauchee of Dews!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAlso, who laid the Rainbow's piers, Also, who leads the docile spheres By withes of supple blue? Whose fingers string the stalactite -Who counts the wampum of the night To see that none is due?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWho built this little Alban House And shut the windows down so close My spirit cannot see? Who'll let me out some gala day With implements to fly away, Passing Pomposity?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d129\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCocoon above! Cocoon below! Stealthy Cocoon, why hide you so What all the world suspect? An hour, and gay on every tree Your secret, perched in ecstasy Defies imprisonment!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAn hour in Chrysalis to pass, Then gay above receding grass A Butterfly to go! A moment to interrogate, Then wiser than a "Surrogate," The Universe to know!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d130\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThese are the days when Birds come back -- A very few -- a Bird or two -- To take a backward look.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThese are the days when skies resume The old -- old sophistries of June -A blue and gold mistake.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh fraud that cannot cheat the Bee -- Almost thy plausibility Induces my belief.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTill ranks of seeds their witness bear -- And softly thro' the altered air Hurries a timid leaf.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOh Sacrament of summer days, Oh Last Communion in the Haze -- Permit a child to join.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThy sacred emblems to partake -- They consecrated bread to take And thine immortal wine!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d131\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBesides the Autumn poets sing A few prosaic days A little this side of the snow And that side of the Haze --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA few incisive Mornings -- A few Ascetic Eves -- Gone -- Mr. Bryant's "Golden Rod" -- And Mr. Thomson's "sheaves."\u13\'0d\u13\'0dStill, is the bustle in the Brook -- Sealed are the spicy valves -- Mesmeric fingers softly touch The Eyes of many Elves --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps a squirrel may remain -- My sentiments to share -- Grant me, Oh Lord, a sunny mind -- Thy windy will to bear!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d132\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI bring an unaccustomed wine To lips long parching Next to mine, And summon them to drink;\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCrackling with fever, they Essay, I turn my brimming eyes away, And come next hour to look.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe hands still hug the tardy glass -- The lips I would have cooled, alas -Are so superfluous Cold --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI would as soon attempt to warm The bosoms where the frost has lain Ages beneath the mould --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome other thirsty there may be To whom this would have pointed me Had it remained to speak --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd so I always bear the cup If, haply, mine may be the drop Some pilgrim thirst to slake --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf, haply, any say to me "Unto the little, unto me," When I at last awake.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d133\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs Children bid the Guest "Good Night" And then reluctant turn - My flowers raise their pretty lips -- Then put their nightgowns on.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs children caper when they wake Merry that it is Morn -- My flowers from a hundred cribs Will peep, and prance again.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d134\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps you'd like to buy a flower, But I could never sell -- If you would like to borrow, Until the Daffodil\u13\'0d\u13\'0dUnties her yellow Bonnet Beneath the village door, Until the Bees, from Clover rows Their Hock, and Sherry, draw,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhy, I will lend until just then, But not an hour more! 135\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWater, is taught by thirst. Land -- by the Oceans passed. Transport -- by throe -- Peace -- by its battles told -- Love, by Memorial Mold -- Birds, by the Snow.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d136\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHave you got a Brook in your little heart, Where bashful flowers blow, And blushing birds go down to drink, And shadows tremble so --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd nobody knows, so still it flows, That any brook is there, And yet your little draught of life Is daily drunken there -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhy, look out for the little brook in March, When the rivers overflow, And the snows come hurrying from the fills, And the bridges often go --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd later, in August it may be -- When the meadows parching lie, Beware, lest this little brook of life, Some burning noon go dry!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d137\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFlowers -- Well -- if anybody Can the ecstasy define -- Half a transport -- half a trouble -- With which flowers humble men: Anybody find the fountain From which floods so contra flow -- I will give him all the Daisies Which upon the hillside blow.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dToo much pathos in their faces For a simple breast like mine -- Butterflies from St. Domingo Cruising round the purple line -- Have a system of aesthetics -- Far superior to mine.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d138\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPigmy seraphs -- gone astray -- Velvet people from Vevay -- Balles from some lost summer day -- Bees exclusive Coterie --}
