Paris could not lay the fold Belted down with Emerald -- Venice could not show a check Of a tint so lustrous meek -- Never such an Ambuscade As of briar and leaf displayed For my little damask maid --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI had rather wear her grace Than an Earl's distinguished face -I had rather dwell like her Than be "Duke of Exeter" -- Royalty enough for me To subdue the Bumblebee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d139\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSoul, Wilt thou toss again? By just such a hazard Hundreds have lost indeed -- But tens have won an all --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAngel's breathless ballot Lingers to record thee -Imps in eager Caucus Raffle for my Soul!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d140 An altered look about the hills -- A Tyrian light the village fills -- A wider sunrise in the morn -- A deeper twilight on the lawn -- A print of a vermillion foot -- A purple finger on the slope -- A flippant fly upon the pane -- A spider at his trade again -- An added strut in Chanticleer -- A flower expected everywhere -- An axe shrill singing in the woods -- Fern odors on untravelled roads -All this and more I cannot tell -- A furtive look you know as well -- And Nicodemus' Mystery Receives its annual reply!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d141\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome, too fragile for winter winds The thoughtful grave encloses -- Tenderly tucking them in from frost Before their feet are cold.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNever the treasures in her nest The cautious grave exposes, Building where schoolboy dare not look, And sportsman is not bold.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis covert have all the children Early aged, and often cold, Sparrow, unnoticed by the Father -- Lambs for whom time had not a fold.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d142\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhose are the little beds, I asked Which in the valleys lie? Some shook their heads, and others smiled -- And no one made reply. Perhaps they did not hear, I said, I will inquire again -- Whose are the beds -- the tiny beds So thick upon the plain?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Tis Daisy, in the shortest -- A little further on -- Nearest the door -- to wake the Ist -Little Leontoden.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Tis Iris, Sir, and Aster -- Anemone, and Bell -- Bartsia, in the blanket red -- And chubby Daffodil.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMeanwhile, at many cradles Her busy foot she plied -- Humming the quaintest lullaby That ever rocked a child.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHush! Epigea wakens! The Crocus stirs her lids -- Rhodora's cheek is crimson, She's dreaming of the woods!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen turning from them reverent -- Their bedtime 'tis, she said -- The Bumble bees will wake them When April woods are red.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d143\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor every Bird a Nest -- Wherefore in timid quest Some little Wren goes seeking round --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWherefore when boughs are free -Households in every tree -- Pilgrim be found?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps a home too high -- Ah Aristocracy! The little Wren desires -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps of twig so fine -Of twine e'en superfine, Her pride aspires --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Lark is not ashamed To build upon the ground Her modest house --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYet who of all the throng Dancing around the sun Does so rejoice?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d144\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe bore it till the simple veins Traced azure on her hand -- Til pleading, round her quiet eyes The purple Crayons stand.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTill Daffodils had come and gone I cannot tell the sum, And then she ceased to bear it -- And with the Saints sat down.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNo more her patient figure At twilight soft to meet -- No more her timid bonnet Upon the village street -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut Crowns instead, and Courtiers -- And in the midst so fair, Whose but her shy -- immortal face Of whom we're whispering here?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d145\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis heart that broke so long -- These feet that never flagged -- This faith that watched for star in vain, Give gently to the dead -- Hound cannot overtake the Hare That fluttered panting, here -- Nor any schoolboy rob the nest Tenderness builded there.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d146\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOn such a night, or such a night, Would anybody care If such a little figure Slipped quiet from its chair --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo quiet -- Oh how quiet, That nobody might know But that the little figure Rocked softer -- to and fro --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOn such a dawn, or such a dawn -- Would anybody sigh That such a little figure Too sound asleep did lie\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor Chanticleer to wake it -- Or stirring house below -- Or giddy bird in orchard -- Or early task to do?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere was a little figure plump For every little knoll -- Busy needles, and spools of thread -And trudging feet from school --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPlaymates, and holidays, and nuts -And visions vast and small -- Strange that the feet so precious charged Should reach so small a goal!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d147 Bless God, he went as soldiers, His musket on his breast -- Grant God, he charge the bravest Of all the martial blest!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPlease God, might I behold him In epauletted white -- I should not fear the foe then -- I should not fear the fight!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d148\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAll overgrown by cunning moss, All interspersed with weed, The little cage of "Currer Bell" In quiet "Haworth" laid.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGathered from many wanderings -Gethsemane can tell Thro' what transporting anguish She reached the Asphodel!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSoft falls the sounds of Eden Upon her puzzled ear - Oh what an afternoon for Heaven, When "Bronte" entered there!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d149\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe went as quiet as the Dew From an Accustomed flower. Not like the Dew, did she return At the Accustomed hour!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe dropt as softly as a star From out my summer's Eve -- Less skillful than Le Verriere It's sorer to believe! 150\u13\'0d\u13\'0dShe died -- this was the way she died. And when her breath was done Took up her simple wardrobe And started for the sun. Her little figure at the gate The Angels must have spied, Since I could never find her Upon the mortal side.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d151\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMute thy Coronation -- Meek my Vive le roi, Fold a tiny courtier In thine Ermine, Sir, There to rest revering Till the pageant by, I can murmur broken, Master, It was I --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d152\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Sun kept stooping -- stooping -- low! The Hills to meet him rose! On his side, what Transaction! On their side, what Repose!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDeeper and deeper grew the stain Upon the window pane -- Thicker and thicker stood the feet Until the Tyrian\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWas crowded dense with Armies -- So gay, so Brigadier -- That I felt martial stirrings Who once the Cockade wore -- Charged from my chimney corner -- But Nobody was there!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d153\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDust is the only Secret -- Death, the only One You cannot find out all about In his "native town."\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNobody know "his Father" -- Never was a Boy -- Hadn't any playmates, Or "Early history" --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIndustrious! Laconic! Punctual! Sedate! Bold as a Brigand! Stiller than a Fleet!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBuilds, like a Bird, too! Christ robs the Nest -- Robin after Robin Smuggled to Rest!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d154\u13\'0d\u13\'0dExcept to Heaven, she is nought. Except for Angels -- lone. Except to some wide-wandering Bee A flower superfluous blown.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dExcept for winds -- provincial. Except by Butterflies Unnoticed as a single dew That on the Acre lies.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe smallest Housewife in the grass, Yet take her from the Lawn And somebody has lost the face That made Existence -- Home!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d155\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Murmur of a Bee A Witchcraft -- yieldeth me -- If any ask me why -- 'Twere easier to die -- Than tell -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Red upon the Hill Taketh away my will -- If anybody sneer -- Take care -- for God is here -- That's all.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Breaking of the Day Addeth to my Degree -- If any ask me how -- Artist -- who drew me so -- Must tell!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d156\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYou love me -- you are sure -- I shall not fear mistake -- I shall not cheated wake -- Some grinning morn -- To find the Sunrise left -- And Orchards -- unbereft -- And Dollie -- gone!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI need not start -- you're sure -- That night will never be -- When frightened -- home to Thee I run -- To find the windows dark -- And no more Dollie -- mark -- Quite none?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBe sure you're sure -- you know -- I'll bear it better now -- If you'll just tell me so -- Than when -- a little dull Balm grown -- Over this pain of mine -- You sting -- again!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d157\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMusicians wrestle everywhere -- All day -- among the crowded air I hear the silver strife -- And -- walking -- long before the morn -- Such transport breaks upon the town I think it that "New Life"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf is not Bird -- it has no nest -- Nor "Band" -- in brass and scarlet -- drest -- Nor Tamborin -- nor Man -- It is not Hymn from pulpit read -- The "Morning Stars" the Treble led On Time's first Afternoon!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome -- say -- it is "the Spheres" -- at play! Some say that bright Majority Of vanished Dames -- and Men! Some -- think it service in the place Where we -- with late -- celestial face -- Please God -- shall Ascertain!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d158\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDying! Dying in the night! Won't somebody bring the light So I can see which way to go Into the everlasting snow?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd "Jesus"! Where is Jesus gone? They said that Jesus -- always came -- Perhaps he doesn't know the House -- This way, Jesus, Let him pass!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSomebody run to the great gate And see if Dollie's coming! Wait! I hear her feet upon the stair! Death won't hurt -- now Dollie's here!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d159\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA little bread -- a crust -- a crumb -- A little trust -- a demijohn -- Can keep the soul alive -- Not portly, mind! but breathing -- warm -- Conscious -- as old Napoleon, The night before the Crown!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA modest lot -- A fame petite -- A brief Campaign of sting and sweet Is plenty! Is enough! A Sailor's business is the shore! A Soldier's -- balls! Who asketh more, Must seek the neighboring life!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d160\u13\'0d\u13\'0dJust lost, when I was saved! Just felt the world go by! Just girt me for the onset with Eternity, When breath blew back, And on the other side I heard recede the disappointed tide!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTherefore, as One returned, I feel Odd secrets of the line to tell! Some Sailor, skirting foreign shores -- Some pale Reporter, from the awful doors Before the Seal!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNext time, to stay! Next time, the things to see By Ear unheard, Unscrutinized by Eye -- Next time, to tarry, While the Ages steal -Slow tramp the Centuries, And the Cycles wheel!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d161\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA feather from the Whippoorwill That everlasting -- sings! Whose galleries -- are Sunrise -- Whose Opera -- the Springs -- Whose Emerald Nest the Ages spin Of mellow -- murmuring thread -- Whose Beryl Egg, what Schoolboys hunt In "Recess" -- Overhead!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d162\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy River runs to thee -Blue Sea! Wilt welcome me? My River wait reply -- Oh Sea -- look graciously -- I'll fetch thee Brooks From spotted nooks -- Say -- Sea -- Take Me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d163\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTho' my destiny be Fustian}
