-- Hers be damask fine -- Tho' she wear a silver apron -- I, a less divine --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dStill, my little Gypsy being I would far prefer, Still, my little sunburnt bosom To her Rosier, For, when Frosts, their punctual fingers On her forehead lay, You and I, and Dr. Holland, Bloom Eternally!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dRoses of a steadfast summer In a steadfast land, Where no Autumn lifts her pencil -- And no Reapers stand!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d164\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMama never forgets her birds, Though in another tree -- She looks down just as often And just as tenderly As when her little mortal nest With cunning care she wove -- If either of her "sparrows fall," She "notices," above.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d165\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Wounded Deer -- leaps highest -I've heard the Hunter tell -- 'Tis but the Ecstasy of death -- And then the Brake is still!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Smitten Rock that gushes! The trampled Steel that springs! A Cheek is always redder Just where the Hectic stings!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMirth is the Mail of Anguish In which it Cautious Arm, Lest anybody spy the blood And "you're hurt" exclaim!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d166 I met a King this afternoon! He had not on a Crown indeed, A little Palmleaf Hat was all, And he was barefoot, I'm afraid!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut sure I am he Ermine wore Beneath his faded Jacket's blue -- And sure I am, the crest he bore Within that Jacket's pocket too!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor 'twas too stately for an Earl -- A Marquis would not go so grand! 'Twas possibly a Czar petite -- A Pope, or something of that kind!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I must tell you, of a Horse My freckled Monarch held the rein -Doubtless an estimable Beast, But not at all disposed to run!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd such a wagon! While I live Dare I presume to see Another such a vehicle As then transported me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTwo other ragged Princes His royal state partook! Doubtless the first excursion These sovereigns ever took!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI question if the Royal Coach Round which the Footmen wait Has the significance, on high, Of this Barefoot Estate!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d167\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo learn the Transport by the Pain As Blind Men learn the sun! To die of thirst -- suspecting That Brooks in Meadows run! To stay the homesick -- homesick feet Upon a foreign shore - Haunted by native lands, the while -And blue -- beloved air!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis is the Sovereign Anguish! This -- the signal woe! These are the patient "Laureates" Whose voices -- trained -- below --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAscend in ceaseless Carol -- Inaudible, indeed, To us -- the duller scholars Of the Mysterious Bard!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d168\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf the foolish, call them "flowers" -- Need the wiser, tell? If the Savants "Classify" them It is just as well!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThose who read the "Revelations" Must not criticize Those who read the same Edition -With beclouded Eyes!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCould we stand with that Old "Moses" -- "Canaan" denied -- Scan like him, the stately landscape On the other side --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDoubtless, we should deem superfluous Many Sciences, Not pursued by learned Angels In scholastic skies!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLow amid that glad Belles lettres Grant that we may stand, Stars, amid profound Galaxies -- At that grand "Right hand"! 169\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn Ebon Box, when years have flown To reverently peer, Wiping away the velvet dust Summers have sprinkled there!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo hold a letter to the light -- Grown Tawny now, with time -- To con the faded syllables That quickened us like Wine!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerhaps a Flower's shrivelled check Among its stores to find - Plucked far away, some morning -- By gallant -- mouldering hand!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA curl, perhaps, from foreheads Our Constancy forgot -- Perhaps, an Antique trinket -- In vanished fashions set!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd then to lay them quiet back -- And go about its care - As if the little Ebon Box Were none of our affair!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d170\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPortraits are to daily faces As an Evening West, To a fine, pedantic sunshine -- In a satin Vest!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d171\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWait till the Majesty of Death Invests so mean a brow! Almost a powdered Footman Might dare to touch it now!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWait till in Everlasting Robes That Democrat is dressed, Then prate about "Preferment" -- And "Station," and the rest!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAround this quiet Courtier Obsequious Angels wait! Full royal is his Retinue! Full purple is his state!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Lord, might dare to lift the Hat To such a Modest Clay Since that My Lord, "the Lord of Lords" Receives unblushingly!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d172\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Tis so much joy! 'Tis so much joy! If I should fail, what poverty! And yet, as poor as I, Have ventured all upon a throw! Have gained! Yes! Hesitated so -- This side the Victory!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLife is but Life! And Death, but Death! Bliss is, but Bliss, and Breath but Breath! And if indeed I fail, At least, to know the worst, is sweet! Defeat means nothing but Defeat, No drearier, can befall!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd if I gain! Oh Gun at Sea! Oh Bells, that in the Steeples be! At first, repeat it slow! For Heaven is a different thing, Conjectured, and waked sudden in -And might extinguish me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d173 A fuzzy fellow, without feet, Yet doth exceeding run! Of velvet, is his Countenance, And his Complexion, dun!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSometime, he dwelleth in the grass! Sometime, upon a bough, From which he doth descend in plush Upon the Passer-by!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAll this in summer. But when winds alarm the Forest Folk, He taketh Damask Residence -- And struts in sewing silk!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen, finer than a Lady, Emerges in the spring! A Feather on each shoulder! You'd scarce recognize him!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy Men, yclept Caterpillar! By me! But who am I, To tell the pretty secret Of the Butterfly!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d174\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAt last, to be identified! At last, the lamps upon thy side The rest of Life to see!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPast Midnight! Past the Morning Star! Past Sunrise! Ah, What leagues there were Between our feet, and Day!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d175\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI have never seen "Volcanoes" -- But, when Travellers tell How those old -- phlegmatic mountains Usually so still --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBear within -- appalling Ordnance, Fire, and smoke, and gun, Taking Villages for breakfast, And appalling Men --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf the stillness is Volcanic In the human face When upon a pain Titanic Features keep their place --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf at length the smouldering anguish Will not overcome -- And the palpitating Vineyard In the dust, be thrown?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf some loving Antiquary, On Resumption Morn, Will not cry with joy "Pompeii"! To the Hills return!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d176\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'm the little "Heart's Ease"! I don't care for pouting skies! If the Butterfly delay Can I, therefore, stay away?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf the Coward Bumble Bee In his chimney corner stay, I, must resoluter be! Who'll apologize for me?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDear, Old fashioned, little flower! Eden is old fashioned, too! Birds are antiquated fellows! Heaven does not change her blue. Nor will I, the little Heart's Ease -- Ever be induced to do! Ah, Necromancy Sweet! Ah, Wizard erudite! Teach me the skill,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat I instil the pain Surgeons assuage in vain, Nor Herb of all the plain Can Heal!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d178\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI cautious, scanned my little life -- I winnowed what would fade From what would last till Heads like mine Should be a-dreaming laid.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI put the latter in a Barn -- The former, blew away. I went one winter morning And lo - my priceless Hay\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWas not upon the "Scaffold" -- Was not upon the "Beam" -- And from a thriving Farmer -- A Cynic, I became.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhether a Thief did it -Whether it was the wind -- Whether Deity's guiltless -- My business is, to find!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo I begin to ransack! How is it Hearts, with Thee? Art thou within the little Barn Love provided Thee? If I could bribe them by a Rose I'd bring them every flower that grows From Amherst to Cashmere! I would not stop for night, or storm -- Or frost, or death, or anyone -- My business were so dear!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf they would linger for a Bird My Tambourin were soonest heard Among the April Woods! Unwearied, all the summer long, Only to break in wilder song When Winter shook the boughs!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat if they hear me! Who shall say That such an importunity May not at last avail?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat, weary of this Beggar's face -- They may not finally say, Yes -- To drive her from the Hall?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d180\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs if some little Arctic flower Upon the polar hem -- Went wandering down the Latitudes Until it puzzled came To continents of summer -- To firmaments of sun - To strange, bright crowds of flowers -- And birds, of foreign tongue! I say, As if this little flower To Eden, wandered in - What then? Why nothing, Only, your inference therefrom! I lost a World - the other day! Has Anybody found? You'll know it by the Row of Stars Around its forehead bound.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Rich man -- might not notice it -- Yet -- to my frugal Eye, Of more Esteem than Ducats -- Oh find it -- Sir -- for me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d182\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I shouldn't be alive When the Robins come, Give the one in Red Cravat, A Memorial crumb.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I couldn't thank you, Being fast asleep, You will know I'm trying Why my Granite lip!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d183\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI've heard an Organ talk, sometimes In a Cathedral Aisle, And understood no word it said -- Yet held my breath, the while --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd risen up -- and gone away, A more Berdardine Girl -- Yet -- know not what was done to me In that old Chapel Aisle.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d184\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA transport one cannot contain May yet a transport be -- Though God forbid it lift the lid -- Unto its Ecstasy!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Diagram -- of Rapture! A sixpence at a Show -- With Holy Ghosts in Cages! The Universe would go!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d185\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Faith" is a fine invention When Gentlemen can see -- But Microscopes are prudent In an Emergency.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d186\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat shall I do -- it whimpers so -- This little Hound within the Heart All day and night with bark and start -- And yet, it will not go -- Would you untie it, were you me -- Would it stop whining -- if to Thee -I sent it -- even now?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt should not tease you -- By your chair -- or, on the mat -- Or if it dare -- to climb your dizzy knee -- Or -- sometimes at your side to run -When you were willing - Shall it come? Tell Carlo - He'll tell me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d187\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow many times these low feet staggered -- Only the soldered mouth can tell - Try -- can you stir the awful rivet -- Try -- can you lift the hasps of steel!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dStroke the cool forehead -- hot so often -- Lift -- if you care -- the listless hair -Handle the adamantine fingers Never a thimble -- more -- shall wear --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBuzz the dull flies -- on the chamber window -- Brave -- shines the sun through the freckled pane -- Fearless -- the cobweb swings from the ceiling -Indolent Housewife -- in Daisies -- lain!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d188\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMake}
