Glory! Wind and Sun -- wilt thee array!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d193\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI shall know why -- when Time is over -- And I have ceased to wonder why -- Christ will explain each separate anguish In the fair schoolroom of the sky --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe will tell me what "Peter" promised -- And I -- for wonder at his woe -- I shall forget the drop of Anguish That scalds me now -- that scalds me now!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d194\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOn this long storm the Rainbow rose -- On this late Morn -- the Sun -- The clouds -- like listless Elephants -Horizons -- straggled down --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Birds rose smiling, in their nests -- The gales -- indeed -- were done -- Alas, how heedless were the eyes -- On whom the summer shone!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe quiet nonchalance of death -- No Daybreak -- can bestir -- The slow -- Archangel's syllables Must awaken her!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d195\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFor this -- accepted Breath -- Through it -- compete with Death -- The fellow cannot touch this Crown -- By it -- my title take -- Ah, what a royal sake To my necessity -- stooped down!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNo Wilderness -- can be Where this attendeth me -- No Desert Noon -- No fear of frost to come Haunt the perennial bloom -- But Certain June!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGet Gabriel -- to tell -- the royal syllable -- Get Saints -- with new -- unsteady tongue -- To say what trance below Most like their glory show -- Fittest the Crown!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d196\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe don't cry -- Tim and I, We are far too grand -- But we bolt the door tight To prevent a friend --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen we hide our brave face Deep in our hand -- Not to cry -- Tim and I -- We are far too grand --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNor to dream -- he and me -- Do we condescend -- We just shut our brown eye To see to the end --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTim -- see Cottages -- But, Oh, so high! Then -- we shake -- Tim and I -- And lest I -- cry --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTim -- reads a little Hymn -- And we both pray -- Please, Sir, I and Tim -- Always lost the way!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe must die -- by and by -- Clergymen say -- Tim -- shall -- if I -- do -I -- too -- if he --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow shall we arrange it -- Tim -- was -- so -- shy? Take us simultaneous -- Lord -- I -- "Tim" -- and Me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d197\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMorning -- is the place for Dew -- Corn -- is made at Noon -- After dinner light -- for flowers -- Dukes -- for Setting Sun!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d198\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAn awful Tempest mashed the air -The clouds were gaunt, and few -- A Black -- as of a Spectre's Cloak Hid Heaven and Earth from view.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe creatures chuckled on the Roofs -- And whistled in the air - And shook their fists -- And gnashed their teeth -- And swung their frenzied hair.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe morning lit -- the Birds arose -The Monster's faded eyes Turned slowly to his native coast -- And peace -- was Paradise!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d199\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'm "wife" -- I've finished that -- That other state -- I'm Czar -- I'm "Woman" now -- It's safer so --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow odd the Girl's life looks Behind this soft Eclipse -- I think that Earth feels so To folks in Heaven -- now --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThis being comfort -- then That other kind -- was pain -- But why compare? I'm "Wife"! Stop there!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPoems No. 200-299\u13\'0d\u13\'0d200\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI stole them from a Bee -- Because -- Thee -- Sweet plea -- He pardoned me!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d201\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTwo swimmers wrestled on the spar -- Until the morning sun - When One -- turned smiling to the land -- Oh God! the Other One!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe stray ships -- passing -- Spied a face -- Upon the waters borne -- With eyes in death -- still begging raised -- And hands -- beseeching -- thrown!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d202\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy Eye is fuller than my vase -- Her Cargo -- is of Dew -- And still -- my Heart -- my Eye outweighs -- East India -- for you!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d203\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe forgot -- and I -- remembered -- 'Twas an everyday affair -- Long ago as Christ and Peter -- "Warmed them" at the "Temple fire."\u13\'0d\u13\'0d"Thou wert with him" -- quoth "the Damsel"? "No" -- said Peter, 'twasn't me -- Jesus merely "looked" at Peter -- Could I do aught else -- to Thee?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d204\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA slash of Blue -- A sweep of Gray -- Some scarlet patches on the way, Compose an Evening Sky -- A little purple -- slipped between -- Some Ruby Trousers hurried on -- A Wave of Gold -- A Bank of Day -- This just makes out the Morning Sky.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d205\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI should not dare to leave my friend, Because -- because if he should die While I was gone -- and I -- too late -Should reach the Heart that wanted me --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I should disappoint the eyes That hunted -- hunted so -- to see -And could not bear to shut until They "noticed" me -- they noticed me --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I should stab the patient faith So sure I'd come -- so sure I'd come -- It listening -- listening -- went to sleep -- Telling my tardy name --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMy Heart would wish it broke before -- Since breaking then -- since breaking then -- Were useless as next morning's sun -- Where midnight frosts -- had lain! The Flower must not blame the Bee -- That seeketh his felicity Too often at her door --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut teach the Footman from Vevay -- Mistress is "not at home" -- to say -- To people -- any more!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d207\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTho' I get home how late -- how late -- So I get home - 'twill compensate -- Better will be the Ecstasy That they have done expecting me -- When Night -- descending -- dumb -- and dark -They hear my unexpected knock - Transporting must the moment be -- Brewed from decades of Agony!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo think just how the fire will burn -Just how long-cheated eyes will turn -- To wonder what myself will say, And what itself, will say to me -- Beguiles the Centuries of way!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d208\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Rose did caper on her cheek -Her Bodice rose and fell -- Her pretty speech -- like drunken men -- Did stagger pitiful --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer fingers fumbled at her work -- Her needle would not go -- What ailed so smart a little Maid -- It puzzled me to know -- Till opposite -- I spied a cheek That bore another Rose -- Just opposite -- Another speech That like the Drunkard goes --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Vest that like her Bodice, danced -To the immortal tune -- Till those two troubled -- little Clocks Ticked softly into one.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d209\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWith thee, in the Desert -- With thee in the thirst - With thee in the Tamarind wood -- Leopard breathes -- at last!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d210\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe thought beneath so slight a film -- Is more distinctly seen - As laces just reveal the surge -- Or mists -- the Apennine\u13\'0d\u13\'0d211\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCome slowly -- Eden! Lips unused to Thee -- Bashful -- sip thy Jessamines -- As the fainting Bee --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dReaching late his flower, Round her chamber hums -- Counts his nectars -- Enters -- and is lost in Balms. Least Rivers -- docile to some sea. My Caspian -- thee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d213\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDid the Harebell loose her girdle To the lover Bee Would the Bee the Harebell hallow Much as formerly?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDid the "Paradise" -- persuaded -- Yield her moat of pearl -- Would the Eden be an Eden, Or the Earl -- an Earl?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d214\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI taste a liquor never brewed -- From Tankards scooped in Pearl -- Not all the Vats upon the Rhine Yield such an Alcohol!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dInebriate of Air -- am I -- And Debauchee of Dew -- Reeling -- thro endless summer days -- From inns of Molten Blue --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen "Landlords" turn the drunken Bee Out of the Foxglove's door -- When Butterflies -- renounce their "drams" -- I shall but drink the more!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTill Seraphs swing their snowy Hats -- And Saints -- to windows run -- To see the little Tippler Leaning against the -- Sun --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d215 What is -- "Paradise" -- Who live there -- Are they "Farmers" -- Do they "hoe" -- Do they know that this is "Amherst" -- And that I -- am coming -- too --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDo they wear "new shoes" -- in "Eden" -- Is it always pleasant -- there -- Won't they scold us -- when we're homesick -- Or tell God -- how cross we are --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYou are sure there's such a person As "a Father" -- in the sky -- So if I get lost -- there -- ever -- Or do what the Nurse calls "die" -- I shan't walk the "Jasper" -- barefoot -- Ransomed folks -- won't laugh at me -- Maybe -- "Eden" a'n't so lonesome As New England used to be!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d216\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSafe in their Alabaster Chambers -- Untouched my Morning And untouched by Noon -- Sleep the meek members of the Resurrection -Rafter of satin, And Roof of stone.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLight laughs the breeze In her Castle above them -- Babbles the Bee in a stolid Ear, Pipe the Sweet Birds in ignorant cadence -- Ah, what sagacity perished here!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d217\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSavior! I've no one else to tell -- And so I trouble thee. I am the one forgot thee so -- Dost thou remember me? Nor, for myself, I came so far -- That were the little load - I brought thee the imperial Heart I had not strength to hold -- The Heart}
