should have been too glad, I see -Too lifted -- for the scant degree Of Life's penurious Round -- My little Circuit would have shamed This new Circumference -- have blamed -- The homelier time behind.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI should have been too saved -- I see -- Too rescued -- Fear too dim to me That I could spell the Prayer I knew so perfect -- yesterday -- That Scalding One -- Sabachthani -Recited fluent -- here -- Earth would have been too much -- I see -- And Heaven -- not enough for me -- I should have had the Joy Without the Fear -- to justify -- The Palm -- without the Calvary -- So Savior -- Crucify -- Defeat -- whets Victory -- they say -- The Reefs -- in old Gethsemane -- Endear the Coast -- beyond! 'Tis Beggars -- Banquets -- can define -- 'Tis Parching -- vitalizes Wine -- "Faith" bleats -- to understand!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d314\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNature -- sometimes sears a Sapling -- Sometimes -- scalps a Tree -- Her Green People recollect it When they do not die -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFainter Leaves -- to Further Seasons -- Dumbly testify -- We -- who have the Souls -- Die oftener -- Not so vitally --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d315\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe fumbles at your Soul As Players at the Keys Before they drop full Music on -- He stuns you by degrees -- Prepares your brittle Nature For the Ethereal Blow By fainter Hammers -- further heard -- Then nearer -- Then so slow Your Breath has time to straighten -Your Brain -- to bubble Cool -- Deals -- One -- imperial -- Thunderbolt -- That scalps your naked Soul -- When Winds take Forests in the Paws -- The Universe -- is still -\u13\'0d\u13\'0d316\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Wind didn't come from the Orchard -- today -- Further than that -- Nor stop to play with the Hay -- Nor joggle a Hat -- He's a transitive fellow -- very -- Rely on that --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf He leave a Bur at the door We know He has climbed a Fir -- But the Fir is Where -- Declare -- Were you ever there?\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf He brings Odors of Clovers -- And that is His business -- not Ours -- Then He has been with the Mowers -- Whetting away the Hours To sweet pauses of Hay -- His Way -- of a June Day --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf He fling Sand, and Pebble -- Little Boys Hats -- and Stubble -- With an occasional Steeple -- And a hoarse "Get out of the way, I say," Who'd be the fool to stay? Would you -- Say -- Would you be the fool to stay?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d317\u13\'0d\u13\'0dJust so -- Jesus -- raps - He -- doesn't weary -- Last -- at the Knocker - And first -- at the Bell. Then -- on divinest tiptoe -- standing -- Might He but spy the lady's soul -- When He -- retires -- Chilled -- or weary -- It will be ample time for -- me -- Patient -- upon the steps -- until then -- Hears! I am knocking -- low at thee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d318\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'll tell you how the Sun rose -- A Ribbon at a time -- The Steeples swam in Amethyst -- The news, like Squirrels, ran -- The Hills untied their Bonnets -- The Bobolinks -- begun -- Then I said softly to myself -- "That must have been the Sun"! But how he set -- I know not -- There seemed a purple stile That little Yellow boys and girls Were climbing all the while -- Till when they reached the other side, A Dominie in Gray -- Put gently up the evening Bars -- And led the flock away --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d319\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe nearest Dream recedes -- unrealized -- The Heaven we chase, Like the June Bee -- before the School Boy, Invites the Race -- Stoops -- to an easy Clover -- Dips -- evades -- teases -- deploys -- Then -- to the Royal Clouds Lifts his light Pinnace - Heedless of the Boy -- Staring -- bewildered -- at the mocking sky -- Homesick for steadfast Honey -- Ah, the Bee flies not That brews that rare variety! 320\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe play at Paste -- Till qualified, for Pearl -- Then, drop the Paste -- And deem ourself a fool --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Shapes -- though -- were similar -- And our new Hands Learned Gem-Tactics - Practicing Sands --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d321\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOf all the Sounds despatched abroad, There's not a Charge to me Like that old measure in the Boughs -- That phraseless Melody -- The Wind does -- working like a Hand, Whose fingers Comb the Sky -- Then quiver down -- with tufts of Tune -- Permitted Gods, and me --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dInheritance, it is, to us - Beyond the Art to Earn -- Beyond the trait to take away By Robber, since the Gain Is gotten not of fingers - And inner than the Bone -- Hid golden, for the whole of Days, And even in the Urn, I cannot vouch the merry Dust Do not arise and play In some odd fashion of its own, Some quainter Holiday, When Winds go round and round in Bands -- And thrum upon the door, And Birds take places, overhead, To bear them Orchestra.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI crave Him grace of Summer Boughs, If such an Outcast be - Who never heard that fleshless Chant -- Rise -- solemn -- on the Tree, As if some Caravan of Sound Off Deserts, in the Sky, Had parted Rank, Then knit, and swept -- In Seamless Company --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d322\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere came a Day at Summer's full, Entirely for me -- I thought that such were for the Saints, Where Resurrections -- be --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Sun, as common, went abroad, The flowers, accustomed, blew, As if no soul the solstice passed That maketh all things new --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe time was scarce profaned, by speech -- The symbol of a word Was needless, as at Sacrament, The Wardrobe -- of our Lord --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dEach was to each The Sealed Church, Permitted to commune this -- time -- Lest we too awkward show At Supper of the Lamb.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Hours slid fast -- as Hours will, Clutched tight, by greedy hands -- So faces on two Decks, look back, Bound to opposing lands --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd so when all the time had leaked, Without external sound Each bound the Other's Crucifix -- We gave no other Bond --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSufficient troth, that we shall rise -- Deposed -- at length, the Grave -- To that new Marriage, Justified -- through Calvaries of Love --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d323\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs if I asked a common Alms, And in my wondering hand A Stranger pressed a Kingdom, And I, bewildered, stand -- As if I asked the Orient Had it for me a Morn -- And it should lift its purple Dikes, And shatter me with Dawn!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d324\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome keep the Sabbath going to Church -- I keep it, staying at Home -- With a Bobolink for a Chorister -- And an Orchard, for a Dome --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome keep the Sabbath in Surplice -I just wear my Wings -- And instead of tolling the Bell, for Church, Our little Sexton -- sings.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGod preaches, a noted Clergyman -- And the sermon is never long, So instead of getting to Heaven, at least -- I'm going, all along.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d325\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOf Tribulation, these are They, Denoted by the White - The Spangled Gowns, a lesser Rank Of Victors -- designate - All these -- did conquer -- But the ones who overcame most times -- Wear nothing commoner than Snow -- No Ornament, but Palms --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSurrender -- is a sort unknown -- On this superior soil -- Defeat -- an outgrown Anguish -- Remembered, as the Mile\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOur panting Ankle barely passed -- When Night devoured the Road -- But we -- stood whispering in the House -- And all we said -- was "Saved"!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d326\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI cannot dance upon my Toes -- No Man instructed me -- But oftentimes, among my mind, A Glee possesseth me,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat had I Ballet knowledge -- Would put itself abroad In Pirouette to blanch a Troupe -- Or lay a Prima, mad,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd though I had no Gown of Gauze -- No Ringlet, to my Hair, Nor hopped to Audiences -- like Birds, One Claw upon the Air,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNor tossed my shape in Eider Balls, Nor rolled on wheels of snow Till I was out of sight, in sound, The House encore me so --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNor any know I know the Art I mention -- easy -- Here -- Nor any Placard boast me -- It's full as Opera -- Before I got my eye put out I liked as well to see -- As other Creatures, that have Eyes And know no other way --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut were it told to me -- Today -- That I might have the sky For mine -- I tell you that my Heart Would split, for size of me --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Meadows -- mine -- The Mountains -- mine -- All Forests -- Stintless Stars -- As much of Noon as I could take Between my finite eyes -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Motions of the Dipping Birds -- The Morning's Amber Road -- For mine -- to look at when I liked -The News would strike me dead --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo safer -- guess -- with just my soul Upon the Window pane -- Where other Creatures put their eyes -- Incautious -- of the Sun --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d328\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Bird came down the Walk -- He did not know I saw -- He bit an Angleworm in halves And ate the fellow, raw,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd then he drank a Dew From a convenient Grass -- And then hopped sidewise to the Wall To let a Beetle pass --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe glanced with rapid eyes That hurried all around -They looked like frightened Beads, I thought -- He stirred his Velvet Head\u13\'0d\u13\'0dLike one in danger, Cautious, I offered him a Crumb And he unrolled his feathers And rowed him softer home --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThan Oars divide the Ocean, Too silver for a seam -- Or Butterflies, off Banks of Noon Leap, plashless as they swim.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d329\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo glad we are -- a Stranger'd deem 'Twas sorry, that we were -- For where the Holiday should be There publishes a Tear - Nor how Ourselves be justified -- Since Grief and Joy are done So similar -- An Optizan Could not decide between --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d330 The Juggler's Hat her Country is -- The Mountain Gorse -- the Bee's! 331\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhile Asters -- On the Hill -- Their Everlasting fashions -- set -- And Covenant Gentians -- Frill! There are two Ripenings -- one -- of sight -- Whose forces Spheric wind Until the Velvet product Drop spicy to the ground -- A homelier maturing -- A process in the Bur -- That teeth of Frosts alone disclose In far October Air.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d333\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Grass so little has to do -- A Sphere of simple Green -- With only Butterflies to brood And Bees to entertain -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd stir all day to pretty Tunes The Breezes fetch along -- And hold the Sunshine in its lap And bow to everything --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd thread the Dews, all night, like Pearls -- And make itself so fine A Duchess were too common For such a noticing --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd even when it dies -- to pass In Odors so divine -- Like Lowly spices, lain to sleep -- Or Spikenards, perishing --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd then, in Sovereign Barns to dwell -- And dream the Days away, The Grass so little has to do I wish I were a Hay --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d334 All the letters I can write Are not fair as this -- Syllables of Velvet -- Sentences of Plush, Depths of Ruby, undrained, Hid, Lip, for}
