f a Sunday, Some manner of the Hair -- A prank nobody knew but them Lost, in the Sepulchre --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow warm, they were, on such a day, You almost feel the date -- So short way off it seems -- And now -- they're Centuries from that --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow pleased they were, at what you said -- You try to touch the smile And dip your fingers in the frost -- When was it -- Can you tell --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYou asked the Company to tea -- Acquaintance -- just a few -- And chatted close with this Grand Thing That don't remember you --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPast Bows, and Invitations -- Past Interview, and Vow -- Past what Ourself can estimate -- That -- makes the Quick of Woe!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d510 It was not Death, for I stood up, And all the Dead, lie down -- It was not Night, for all the Bells Put out their Tongues, for Noon.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt was not Frost, for on my Flesh I felt Siroccos -- crawl - Nor Fire -- for just my Marble feet Could keep a Chancel, cool --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd yet, it tasted, like them all, The Figures I have seen Set orderly, for Burial, Reminded me, of mine --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs if my life were shaven, And fitted to a frame, And could not breathe without a key, And 'twas like Midnight, some -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen everything that ticked -- has stopped -- And Space stares all around -- Or Grisly frosts -- first Autumn morns, Repeal the Beating Ground --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut, most, like Chaos - Stopless -- cool -- Without a Change, or Spar -- Or even a Report of Land -- To justify -- Despair.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d511\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf you were coming in the Fall, I'd brush the Summer by With half a smile, and half a spurn, As Housewives do, a Fly.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf I could see you in a year, I'd wind the months in balls -- And put them each in separate Drawers, For fear the numbers fuse -- If only Centuries, delayed, I'd count them on my Hand, Subtracting, till my fingers dropped Into Van Dieman's Land.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf certain, when this life was out -- That