at men, must slake in Wilderness -- And in the Desert -- cloy -- An instinct for the Hoar, the Bald -- Lapland's -- necessity -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Hemlock's nature thrives -- on cold -- The Gnash of Northern winds Is sweetest nutriment -- to him -- His best Norwegian Wines --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo satin Races -- he is nought -- But Children on the Don, Beneath his Tabernacles, play, And Dnieper Wrestlers, run.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d526\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo hear an Oriole sing May be a common thing -- Or only a divine.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt is not of the Bird Who sings the same, unheard, As unto Crowd --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Fashion of the Ear Attireth that it hear In Dun, or fair --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo whether it be Rune, Or whether it be none Is of within.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe "Tune is in the Tree --" The Skeptic -- showeth me -- "No Sir! In Thee!" 527\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo put this World down, like a Bundle -- And walk steady, away, Requires Energy -- possibly Agony -- 'Tis the Scarlet way\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTrodden with straight renunciation By the Son of God -- Later, his faint Confederates Justify the Road --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFlavors of that old Crucifixion -- Filaments of Bloom, Pontius Pilate sowed -- Strong Clusters, from Barabbas' Tomb --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSacrament, Saints partook before us -- Patent, every drop, With the Brand of the Gentile Drinker Who indorsed the Cup --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d528\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMine -- by the Right of the White Election! Mine -- by the Royal Seal! Mine -- by the Sign in the Scarlet prison -- Bars -- cannot conceal!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dMine -- here -- in Vision -- and in Veto! Mine -- by the Grave's Repeal -- Tilted -- Confirmed -- Delirious Charter! Mine -- long as Ages steal!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d529\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI'm sorry for the Dead -- Today -- It's such congenial times Old Neighbors have at fences -- It's time o' year for Hay.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd Broad -- Sunburned Acquaintance Discourse between the Toil -- And laugh, a homely species That makes the Fences smile --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIt seems so straight to lie away From all of the noise of Fields -- The Busy Carts -- the fragrant Cocks -- The Mower's Metre -- Steals --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Trouble lest they're homesick -- Those Farmers -- and their Wives -- Set separate from the Farming -- And all the Neighbors' lives --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Wonder if the Sepulchre Don't feel a lonesome way -- When Men -- and Boys -- and Carts -- and June, Go down the Fields to "Hay" --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d530\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYou cannot put a Fire out -- A Thing that can ignite Can go, itself, without a Fan -- Upon the slowest Night --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dYou cannot fold a Flood -- And put it in a Drawer -- Because the Winds would find it out -And tell your Cedar Floor --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d531\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe dream -- it is good we are dreaming -- It would hurt us -- were we awake -- But since it is playing -- kill us, And we are playing -- shriek --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhat harm? Men die -- externally -- It is a truth -- of Blood -- But we -- are dying in Drama -- And Drama -- is never dead --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCautious -- We jar each other -- And either -- open the eyes -- Lest the Phantasm -- prove the Mistake -- And the livid Surprise\u13\'0d\u13\'0dCool us to Shafts of Granite -- With just an Age -- and Name -- And perhaps a phrase in Egyptian -- It's prudenter -- to dream --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d532\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI tried to think a lonelier Thing Than any I had seen -- Some Polar Expiation -- An Omen in the Bone Of Death's tremendous nearness --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI probed Retrieverless things My Duplicate -- to borrow -- A Haggard Comfort springs\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFrom the belief that Somewhere -- Within the Clutch of Thought -- There dwells one other Creature Of Heavenly Love -- forgot --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI plucked at our Partition As One should pry the Walls -- Between Himself -- and Horror's Twin -- Within Opposing Cells -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI almost strove to clasp his Hand, Such Luxury -- it grew -- That as Myself -- could pity Him