Pharaoh -- I have a Navy in the West Would pierce his Columns thro' -- Guileless, yet of such Glory fine That all along the Line Is it, or is it not, divine -- The Eye inquires with a sigh That Earth sh'd be so big -- What Exultation in the Woe -- What Wine in the fatigue! 1643\u13\'0d\u13\'0dExtol thee -- could I? Then I will By saying nothing new -- But just the truest truth That thou art heavenly.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPerceiving thee is evidence That we are of the sky Partaking thee a guaranty Of immortality\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1644\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSome one prepared this mighty show To which without a Ticket go The nations and the Days --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDisplayed before the simplest Door That all may witness it and more, The pomp of summer Days.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1645\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Ditch is dear to the Drunken man For is it not his Bed -- His Advocate -- his Edifice? How safe his fallen Head In her disheveled Sanctity -- Above him is the sky - Oblivion bending over him And Honor leagues away.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1646\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhy should we hurry -- why indeed? When every way we fly We are molested equally By immortality. No respite from the inference That this which is begun, Though where its labors lie A bland uncertainty Besets the sight This mighty night --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1647\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOf Glory not a Beam is left But her Eternal House -- The Asterisk is for the Dead, The Living, for the Stars --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1648\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe immortality she gave We borrowed at her Grave -- For just one Plaudit famishing, The Might of Human love --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1649\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Cap of Lead across the sky Was tight and surly drawn We could not find the mighty Face The Figure was withdrawn --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Chill came up as from a shaft Our noon became a well A Thunder storm combines the charms Of Winter and of Hell.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1650 A lane of Yellow led the eye Unto a Purple Wood Whose soft inhabitants to be Surpasses solitude If Bird the silence contradict Or flower presume to show In that low summer of the West Impossible to know --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1651\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Word made Flesh is seldom And tremblingly partook Nor then perhaps reported But have I not mistook Each one of us has tasted With ecstasies of stealth The very food debated To our specific strength -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Word that breathes distinctly Has not the power to die Cohesive as the Spirit It may expire if He -- "Made Flesh and dwelt among us" Could condescension be Like this consent of Language This loved Philology.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1652\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAdvance is Life's condition The Grave but a Relay Supposed to be a terminus That makes it hated so -\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Tunnel is not lighted Existence with a wall Is better we consider Than not exist at all -- As we pass Houses musing slow If they be occupied So minds pass minds If they be occupied\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1654\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBeauty crowds me till I die Beauty mercy have on me But if I expire today Let it be in sight of thee -\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1655\u13\'0d\u13\'0dConferring with myself My stranger disappeared Though first upon a berry fat Miraculously fared How paltry looked my cares My practise how absurd Superfluous my whole career Beside this travelling Bird\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1656\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDown Time's quaint stream Without an oar We are enforced to sail Our Port a secret Our Perchance a Gale What Skipper would Incur the Risk What Buccaneer would ride Without a surety from the Wind Or schedule of the Tide --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1657\u13\'0d\u13\'0dEden is that old-fashioned House We dwell in every day Without suspecting our abode Until we drive away.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow fair on looking back, the Day We sauntered from the Door -- Unconscious our returning, But discover it no more.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1658\u13\'0d\u13\'0dEndanger it, and the Demand Of tickets for a sigh Amazes the Humility Of Credibility --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dRecover it to Nature And that dejected Fleet Find Consternation's Carnival Divested of its Meat.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1659\u13\'0d\u13\'0dFame is a fickle food Upon a shifting plate Whose table once a Guest but not The second time is set.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhose crumbs the crows inspect And with ironic caw Flap past it to the Farmer's Corn -- Men eat of it and die. Glory is that bright tragic thing That for an instant Means Dominion -- Warms some poor name That never felt the Sun, Gently replacing In oblivion --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1661\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGuest am I to have Light my northern room Why to cordiality so averse to come Other friends adjourn Other bonds decay Why avoid so narrowly My fidelity --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1662\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe went by sleep that drowsy route To the surmising Inn -- At day break to begin his race Or ever to remain --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1663\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHis mind of man, a secret makes I meet him with a start He carries a circumference In which I have no part --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOr even if I deem I do He otherwise may know Impregnable to inquest However neighborly --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1664\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI did not reach Thee But my feet slip nearer every day Three Rivers and a Hill to cross One Desert and a Sea I shall not count the journey one When I am telling thee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTwo deserts, but the Year is cold So that will help the sand One desert crossed -- The second one Will feel as cool as land Sahara is too little price To pay for thy Right hand.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Sea comes last -- Step merry, feet, So short we have to go -- To play together we are prone, But we must labor now, The last shall be the lightest load That we have had to draw.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Sun goes crooked - That is Night Before he makes the bend. We must have passed the Middle Sea -- Almost we wish the End Were further off -- Too great it seems So near the Whole to stand.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWe step like Plush, We stand like snow, The waters murmur new. Three rivers and the Hill are passed -Two deserts and the sea! Now Death usurps my Premium And gets the look at Thee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1665\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI know of people in the Grave Who would be very glad To know the news I know tonight If they the chance had had.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Tis this expands the least event And swells the scantest deed -- My right to walk upon the Earth If they this moment had.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1666\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI see thee clearer for the Grave That took thy face between No Mirror could illumine thee Like that impassive stone --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI know thee better for the Act That made thee first unknown The stature of the empty nest Attests the Bird that's gone.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1667\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI watcher her face to see which way She took the awful news -- Whether she died before she heard Or in protracted bruise Remained a few slow years with us -Each heavier than the last -- A further afternoon to fail, As Flower at fall of Frost. If I could tell how glad I was I should not be so glad - But when I cannot make the Force, Nor mould it into Word, I know it is a sign That new Dilemna be From mathematics further off Than for Eternity.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1669\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn snow thou comest -- Thou shalt go with the resuming ground, The sweet derision of the crow, And Glee's advancing sound.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn fear thou comest -- Thou shalt go at such a gait of joy That man anew embark to live Upon the depth of thee.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1670\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn Winter in my Room I came upon a Worm -- Pink, lank and warm -- But as he was a worm And worms presume Not quite with him at home -- Secured him by a string To something neighboring And went along.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Trifle afterward A thing occurred I'd not believe it if I heard But state with creeping blood -- A snake with mottles rare Surveyed my chamber floor In feature as the worm before But ringed with power --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe very string with which I tied him -- too When he was mean and new That string was there --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI shrank -- "How fair you are"! Propitiation's claw -- "Afraid," he hissed "Of me"? "No cordiality" -- He fathomed me -- Then to a Rhythm Slim Secreted in his Form As Patterns swim Projected him.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat time I flew Both eyes his way Lest he pursue Nor ever ceased to run Till in a distant Town Towns on from mine I set me down This was a dream.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1671\u13\'0d\u13\'0dJudgment is justest When the Judged, His action laid away, Divested is of every Disk But his sincerity.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHonor is then the safest hue In a posthumous Sun -- Not any color will endure That scrutiny can burn. Lightly stepped a yellow star To its lofty place -- Loosed the Moon her silver hat From her lustral Face - All of Evening softly lit As an Astral Hall -- Father, I observed to Heaven, You are punctual.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1673\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNature can do no more She has fulfilled her Dyes Whatever Flower fail to come Of other Summer days Her crescent reimburse If other Summers be Nature's imposing negative Nulls opportunity --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1674\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNot any sunny tone From any fervent zone Find entrance there -- Better a grave of Balm Toward human nature's home -- And Robins near -- Than a stupendous Tomb Proclaiming to the Gloom How dead we are --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1675 Of this is Day composed A morning and a noon A Revelry unspeakable And then a gay unknown Whose Pomps allure and spurn And dower and deprive And penury for Glory Remedilessly leave.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1676\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOf Yellow was the outer Sky In Yellower Yellow hewn Till Saffron in Vermilion slid Whose seam could not be shewn.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1677\u13\'0d\u13\'0dOn my volcano grows the Grass A meditative spot -- An acre for a Bird to choose Would be the General thought --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow red the Fire rocks below -- How insecure the sod Did I disclose Would populate with awe my solitude.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1678\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPeril as a Possesssion 'Tis Good to hear Danger disintegrates Satiety There's Basis there -- Begets an awe That searches Human Nature's creases As clean as Fire. Rather arid delight If Contentment accrue Make an abstemious Ecstasy Not so good as joy --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBut Rapture's Expense Must not be incurred With a tomorrow knocking And the Rent unpaid --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1680\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSometimes with the Heart Seldom with the Soul Scarcer once with the Might Few -- love at all.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1681\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSpeech is one symptom of Affection And Silence one -- The perfectest communication Is heard of none --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dExists and its indorsement Is had within -- Behold, said the Apostle, Yet had not seen!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1682\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSummer begins to have the look Peruser of enchanting Book Reluctantly but sure perceives A gain upon the backward leaves --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAutumn begins to be inferred By millinery of the cloud Or deeper color in the shawl That wraps the everlasting hill.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe eye begins its avarice A meditation chastens speech Some Dyer of a distant tree Resumes his gaudy industry.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dConclusion is the course of All At most to be perennial And then elude stability Recalls to immortality.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1683\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThat she forgot me was the least I felt it second pain That I was worthy to forget Was}
