ond The majesties of Earth.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe soul her "Not at Home" Inscribes upon the flesh -- And takes her fair aerial gait Beyond the hope of touch.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1692\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe right to perish might be thought An undisputed right -- Attempt it, and the Universe Upon the opposite Will concentrate its officers -- You cannot even die But nature and mankind must pause To pay you scrutiny.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1693\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe Sun retired to a cloud A Woman's shawl as big -- And then he sulked in mercury Upon a scarlet log -- The drops on Nature's forehead stood Home flew the loaded bees -- The South unrolled a purple fan And handed to the trees.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1694\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe wind drew off Like hungry dogs Defeated of a bone -- Through fissures in Volcanic cloud The yellow lightning shone -- The trees held up Their mangled limbs Like animals in pain -- When Nature falls upon herself Beware an Austrian.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1695\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThere is a solitude of space A solitude of sea A solitude of death, but these Society shall be Compared with that profounder site That polar privacy A soul admitted to itself -- Finite infinity.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1696\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThese are the days that Reindeer love And pranks the Northern star -- This is the Sun's objective, And Finland of the Year.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1697\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThey talk as slow as Legends grow No mushroom is their mind But foliage of sterility Too stolid for the wind --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThey laugh as wise as Plots of Wit Predestined to unfold The point with bland prevision Portentously untold.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1698 'Tis easier to pity those when dead That which pity previous Would have saved -- A Tragedy enacted Secures Applause That Tragedy enacting Too seldom does.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1699\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo do a magnanimous thing And take oneself by surprise If oneself is not in the habit of him Is precisely the finest of Joys --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dNot to do a magnanimous thing Notwithstanding it never be known Notwithstanding it cost us existence once Is Rapture herself spurn --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dPoems No. 1700-1775\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1700\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo tell the Beauty would decrease To state the Spell demean -- There is a syllable-less Sea Of which it is the sign - My will endeavors for its word And fails, but entertains A Rapture as of Legacies -- Of introspective Mines --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1701\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo their apartment deep No ribaldry may creep Untumbled this abode By any man but God --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1702\u13\'0d\u13\'0dToday or this noon She dwelt so close I almost touched her -Tonight she lies Past neighborhood And bough and steeple, Now past surmise.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1703\u13\'0d\u13\'0d'Twas comfort in her Dying Room To hear the living Clock -- A short relief to have the wind Walk boldly up and knock -- Diversion from the Dying Theme To hear the children play -- But wrong the more That these could live And this of ours must die.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1704\u13\'0d\u13\'0dUnto a broken heart No other one may go Without the high prerogative Itself hath suffered too.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1705\u13\'0d\u13\'0dVolcanoes be in Sicily And South America I judge from my Geography -- Volcanos nearer here A Lava step at any time Am I inclined to climb -- A Crater I may contemplate Vesuvius at Home.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1706\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWhen we have ceased to care The Gift is given For which we gave the Earth And mortgaged Heaven But so declined in worth 'Tis ignominy now To look upon --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1707 Winter under cultivation Is as arable as Spring.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1708\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWitchcraft has not a Pedigree 'Tis early as our Breath And mourners meet it going out The moment of our death --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1709\u13\'0d\u13\'0dWith sweetness unabated Informed the hour had come With no remiss of triumph The autumn started home\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer home to be with Nature As competition done By influential kinsmen Invited to return --\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIn supplements of Purple An adequate repast In heavenly reviewing Her residue be past --\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1710\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA curious Cloud surprised the Sky, 'Twas like a sheet with Horns; The sheet was Blue -- The Antlers Gray -- It almost touched the lawns.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo low it leaned -- then statelier drew -- And trailed like robes away, A Queen adown a satin aisle Had not the majesty.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1711\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA face devoid of love or grace, A hateful, hard, successful face, A face with which a stone Would feel as thoroughly at ease As were they old acquaintances -- First time together thrown.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1712\u13\'0d\u13\'0dA Pit -- but Heaven over it -- And Heaven beside, and Heaven abroad, And yet a Pit -- With Heaven over it.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dTo stir would be to slip -To look would be to drop -- To dream -- to sap the Prop That holds my chances up. Ah! Pit! With Heaven over it!\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThe depth is all my thought -- I dare not ask my feet -- 'Twould start us where we sit So straight you'd scarce suspect It was a Pit -- with fathoms under it -- Its Circuit just the same. Seed -- summer -- tomb -- Whose Doom to whom?\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1713\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAs subtle as tomorrow That never came, A warrant, a conviction, Yet but a name.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1714\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBy a departing light We see acuter, quite, Than by a wick that stays. There's something in the flight That clarifies the sight And decks the rays.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1715\u13\'0d\u13\'0dConsulting summer's clock, But half the hours remain. I ascertain it with a shock -- I shall not look again. The second half of joy Is shorter than the first. The truth I do not dare to know I muffle with a jest.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1716\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDeath is like the insect Menacing the tree, Competent to kill it, But decoyed may be.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dBait it with the balsam, Seek it with the saw, Baffle, if it cost you Everything you are.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThen, if it have burrowed Out of reach of skill -- Wring the tree and leave it, 'Tis the vermin's will.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1717\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDid life's penurious length Italicize its sweetness, The men that daily live Would stand so deep in joy That it would clog the cogs Of that revolving reason Whose esoteric belt Protects our sanity.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1718\u13\'0d\u13\'0dDrowning is not so pitiful As the attempt to rise Three times, 'tis said, a sinking man Comes up to face the skies, And then declines forever To that abhorred abode, Where hope and he part company -- For he is grasped of God. The Maker's cordial visage, However good to see, Is shunned, we must admit it, Like an adversity.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1719\u13\'0d\u13\'0dGod is indeed a jealous God -- He cannot bear to see That we had rather not with Him But with each other play.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1720 Had I known that the first was the last I should have kept it longer. Had I known that the last was the first I should have drunk it stronger. Cup, it was your fault, Lip was not the liar. No, lip, it was yours, Bliss was most to blame.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1721\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHe was my host -- he was my guest, I never to this day If I invited him could tell, Or he invited me.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dSo infinite our intercourse So intimate, indeed, Analysis as capsule seemed To keeper of the seed.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1722\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHer face was in a bed of hair, Like flowers in a plot -- Her hand was whiter than the sperm That feeds the sacred light. Her tongue more tender than the tune That totters in the leaves -- Who hears may be incredulous, Who witnesses, believes.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1723\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHigh from the earth I heard a bird, He trod upon the trees As he esteemed them trifles, And then he spied a breeze, And situated softly Upon a pile of wind Which in a perturbation Nature had left behind. A joyous going fellow I gathered from his talk Which both of benediction And badinage partook. Without apparent burden I subsequently learned He was the faithful father Of a dependent brood. And this untoward transport His remedy for care. A contrast to our respites. How different we are!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1724\u13\'0d\u13\'0dHow dare the robins sing, When men and women hear Who since they went to their account Have settled with the year! -- Paid all that life had earned In one consummate bill, And now, what life or death can do Is immaterial. Insulting is the sun To him whose mortal light Beguiled of immortality Bequeaths him to the night. Extinct be every hum In deference to him Whose garden wrestles with the dew, At daybreak overcome!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1725\u13\'0d\u13\'0dI took one Draught of Life -- I'll tell you what I paid -Precisely an existence -The market price, they said.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dThey weighed me, Dust by Dust -- They balanced Film with Film, Then handed me my Being's worth -- A single Dram of Heaven!\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1726\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf all the griefs I am to have Would only come today, I am so happy I believe They'd laugh and run away.\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf all the joys I am to have Would only come today, They could not be so big as this That happens to me now.\u13\'0d\u13\'0d1727\u13\'0d\u13\'0dIf ever the lid gets off my head And lets the brain away The fellow will go where he belonged -- Without a hint from me,\u13\'0d\u13\'0dAnd the world -- if the world be looking on -- Will see how far from home It is possible}
